<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dennis Wins Bus Export Orders from Hongkong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Export orders worth 70 million
pounds (112 million US dollars) have been placed with Dennis
Specialist Vehicles by three of Hongkong's biggest bus operators,
according to an announcement here today.
</P>
<P>
"Dennis has been supplying double-deck buses to Hongkong for
almost 20 years without a break," said Roger Heard, Dennis sales
and marketing director, "which gives us a track record no other
chassis manufacturer can match."
</P>
<P>
"With the Trident we are now taking the lead in the supply of
accessible double-deckers, which we believe will ultimately
strengthen our position as supplier of buses to mainland China,
where demand for transport is growing rapidly," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 112 million US dollars order is divided between two new
Dennis double-deck models -- the trend-setting low-floor Trident,
and an improved three-axle Dragon powered by the latest
low-emission Cummins M11 engine, which is also used in the
Trident.
</P>
<P>
The three companies which have placed orders are all existing
Dennis users. Among them, the Kowloon Motor Bus Company runs the
world's biggest Dennis Fleet (with more than 1,600 in daily
service) and is adding to this almost 350 Tridents and Dragons.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Citybus has also ordered low-floor Tridents, while the
China Motor Bus Company is taking a quantity of Dragons.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the deal, the British Motor Industry said in a
statement: "The orders for 421 double-decker buses demonstrate
the Hongkong bus operators' commitment to improving services after
the colony's return to mainland China."
</P>
<P>
"They provide Dennis with an ideal opportunity to strengthen
its relationships with potential new customers in China, where the
expanding economy is creating new demands for transport," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
