<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Praises Canada for Efforts to Bolster Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 14 (Xinhua) - Canada is trying to get all the
parties concerned to the negotiating table and help overcome the
obstacles facing the stalemated Middle East peace process,
visiting Canadian Middle East peace coordinator Andrew Robinson
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Robinson made the remarks while meeting with Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali, who praised Canada for its
contributions to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Radio Jordan, Majali and Robinson reviewed the
efforts underway to get the peace process back on track and the
issue of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister underlined that the refugee issue could only
be settled when the Palestinians regained their political identity
through the establishment of their own state on their national
soil.
</P>
<P>
Canada has been playing a minor role in speeding up the peace
process. However, the Canadian participation is expected to be
effective to some extent, since King Hussein's recent
visit to the United States produced no concrete results for the
peace mark.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian move came after the U.S. has shunned away from
efforts to bring the peace process back on track and to defuse the
Arab-Israeli tension caused by Israeli government's building of a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
