<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Encouraged by Declarations of Mobutu, Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is
encouraged by the declarations made last weekend by Zairian
President Mobutu Sese Seko and Zairian rebel leader Laurent-Desire
Kabila that they are likely to hold direct talks.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said
that France "wants to consider the declarations of President
Mobutu" and those of Kabila "as not excluding the possibility of
a meeting, and that appeared encouraging to us."
</P>
<P>
"The conclusion of the ceasefire as well as the pursuit of
political dialogue between the Zairian parties are necessary and
urgent," said the spokesman, adding that France "strongly
encourages the rapid resumption of inter-Zairian talks."
</P>
<P>
Mobutu said last Saturday that he was ready to meet Kabila if
he asked for such a meeting in a polite way, and rejected an
ultimatum by Kabila who asked Mobutu to meet him within three days
to negotiate the terms for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
The "foreign minister" of the Zairian rebels, Bizima Karaha,
said on Sunday that Kabila would travel very soon -- probably to
South Africa -- to "dynamize" negotiation with the Zairian
government, and that if necessary, he would meet Mobutu.
</P>
<P>
The delegates of Mobutu and Kabila held talks for four days
last week in South Africa under the mediation of the United
Nations special envoy for the Great Lakes region, Mohammed
Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
France last Friday called for a meeting between Mobutu and
Kabila, which Paris said "would contribute to facilitating a
pacific solution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
