<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Current Accounts Deficit Increases in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece's current accounts deficit
reached 4.5 billion U.S. dollars this year, compared to 2.8
billion dollars last year, figures released by the bank of Greece
said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the increase mainly to the trade
deficit rise and invisible surplus drop.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Greece's trade deficit has reportedly increased by 1.2
billion dollars while the invisible surplus dropped by 469 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the bank said, inflows of private capital
increased this year to reach 7.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In March, exchange reserves in the country reached a record
high, totaling 19.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
