<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Economy Grows, Signals End of Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's gross domestic product
(GDP) grew year-on-year by 0.2 percent in the first quarter, in a
further sign that the country's six-year slump may be over.
</P>
<P>
The small rise in GDP for the first quarter over the first
quarter of 1996, quoted by the State Statistics Committee, comes
three days after figures showing industrial output rose 0.7
percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
Services still accounted for more than half of GDP, rising from
50.5 percent in the first quarter of 1996 to 51.8 percent, but the
proportion of GDP accounted for by manufacturing rose from 36.8
percent to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
GDP in Russia has fallen every year since the collapse of the
Soviet Union in 1991 as the country has undergone painful
reforms.
</P>
<P>
But GDP and industrial output have risen every month so far
this year compared with year-earlier comparisons and government
officials have forecast that GDP will rise by 2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the World Bank, in a report issued last month, forecast
zero growth this year, and two percent growth in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Output, Input Prices Both Fall in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Both Britain's output prices and
input prices fell unexpectedly last month, boosting the
re-election campaign of the ruling Conservative Party, which still
lags far behind the opposition Labor Party in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released today by the Office for National
Statistics (ONS), output, or factory gate prices fell by 0.1
percent in March on the previous month, giving a 1.0 percent
increase on the year, against a forecast of a 0.1 percent rise for
the month.
</P>
<P>
This compared with a 0.1 percent monthly fall and a 1.2 percent
year-on-year rise in February.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, input, or raw materials prices fell by 0.5 percent
on the month and 7.6 percent on the year.
</P>
<P>
UK government, facing the general election on May 1, welcomed
the data, saying that the figures were proof that its policies had
brought about a sound economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Clarke, Chancellor of the Exchequer, said the figures
showed "Conservative policies have made Britain a low inflation
economy", adding "we are achieving sustainable growth without
either inflation or balance of payments problems, building
prosperity that lasts".
</P>
<P>
Although some economists said that the data indicated that
inflation is not an issue people should be worrying about, others
believed that interest rates would probably still have to rise
after the general election.
</P>
<P>
They argued that today's data only suggest that inflation is
not a real problem for the manufacturing sector, a relatively
small part of the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the service sector, making up a far greater part of the
whole economy, has already showed signs of inflationary pressures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
