<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Rid Schools of Cigarette Automats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The federation of German cigarette
automats companies (BDTA) today agreed to introduce self-imposed
restrictions to dismantle all cigarette automats within or near
schools as a measure to protect youngsters from tobacco abuse.
</P>
<P>
After intensive negotiations with the German Health Ministry,
the BDTA agreed to dismantle all cigarette automats located in
schools and youth centers within three months.
</P>
<P>
The federation also promised not to set up new automats within
a range of 50 meters in sight of the entrances of schools and
youth centers and in streets next to these facilities. Cigarette
already exists in those areas should be eliminated within three
years.
</P>
<P>
Violators of the rule would be fined with maximum 1,000 marks,
about 580 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The BDTA represents about 90 percent of all cigarette automat
makers in Germany. The Health Ministry also expects those
companies which are not BDTA members also to participate in the
self-imposed restrictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
