<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Urge World Governments to Meet Earth Summit Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Parliamentarians from 134 countries
today called on governments worldwide to abide by the committments
they made at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992 to
safeguard the world's environment.
</P>
<P>
The 600 parliamentarians attending the six-day
Inter-Parliamentary Union conference here today urged
parliamentarians to pressurize their governments to set concrete
goals and deadlines to meet the agreements made at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The conference warned that failure to act could cause the
destruction of humanity and called for changes in the world's
production and consumption patterns to ensure sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
Delegates also adopted resolutions calling for cooperation to
ensure world and regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The delegates urged parliaments all over the world to intensify
parliamentary diplomacy based on the universal principles of
equality, non-interference in other's internal affairs, respect
for territorial integrity, the independence of all states and
respect for human rights.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese National People's Congress (NPC) delegation led by
Wang Guangying, vice chairman of the NPC Standing Committee,
attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference also accepted membership requests from the
parliaments of Cambodia, Georgia, Tajikistan and Niger to bring
the total number of IPU members to 138.
</P>
<P>
The next IPU conference is expected to be held in Cairo, Egypt,
in September.
</P>
<P>
The IPU, which has 134 member countries, is a focal point for
world-wide parliamentary dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
