<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Press Bill Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 15 (Xinhua)-- The Sierra Leone Association of
Journalists (SLAJ) Monday stepped up its attack on the press bill
to be debated by parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The association in a statement issued Monday, the second
within 36 hours, said the bill "reflects a slant in favour of
political rather than professional interest".
</P>
<P>
SLAJ's president Frank Kposowa in an interview with Xinhua
accused information minister Abdul Thorlu-Bangura of "betraying
the confidence of SLAJ which had the feeling it enjoyed the
cooperation with the authorities to effect the necessary
improvement of press laws".
</P>
<P>
Information minister Thorlu-Bangura in an interview said the
bill "is necessary to bring sanity to the profession and save the
trade from being swamped by dead woods".
</P>
<P>
Opposition to the bill has also come in from the Pan African
Association for Human Rights and Democracy which advises the
government to allow SLAJ "to reslove problems within the armbit
of journalism".
</P>
<P>
"The bill is a direct step to muzzle if not censure the
press", the association says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
