<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Young-sam to decide whether to grant Amnesty to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior South Korean official today
stressed that only President Kim Young-sam can decide whether and
when to grant a pardon to former presidents Chun Doo-hwan and Roh
Tae-woo.
</P>
<P>
The granting of amnesty is an authority and privilege held only
by the president, said Kang In-sup, presidential secretary for
political affairs.
</P>
<P>
"It is too early to talk about whether and when the president
will pardon the former presidents," said Kang in response to some
news reports that the ruling camp and presidential secretariat
intend to grant a presidential amnesty to Chun and Roh.
</P>
<P>
The move will help conclude President Kim's term in
reconciliation and provide a momentum for national unity, said
these reports.
</P>
<P>
"At present, the president is not considering the matter," said
Kang.
</P>
<P>
Chun and Roh, both jailed for mutiny, treason and corruption
charges, face a final verdict by the Supreme Court on April 17.
</P>
<P>
With the ruling by the highest court approaching, some
presidential aspirants of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP) have
recently called for the granting of a special amnesty to the
former presidents.
</P>
<P>
The recent Hanbo scandal in which several ruling party
representatives and government officials were involved defaced the
NKP and the government.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who initiated the trials, is believed by most
mass-communications to have the matter better concluded by
granting pardons to the former presidents before his five-year
term ends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
