<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Suspends Panel on Helms-Burton Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
decided to delay submitting its complaint against the United
States' Helms-Burton Bill to a WTO trade dispute panel.
</P>
<P>
The EU was due to submit its complaint against U.S. legislation
penalizing foreign companies trading with or investing in Cuba to
the WTO today.
</P>
<P>
But after a preliminary deal between the two sides last Friday,
in which the U.S. agreed to modify the law, known as the
Helms-Burton Bill, EU Trade Commission Sir Leon Brittan said the
EU would suspend the submission of its complaint and start talks
with the U.S. over the dispute.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU has not ruled out reviving the complaint and
Brittan emphasised that this was only a preliminary agreement. He
said the EU hoped to sign a final agreement with the U.S. in
October.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress passed the Helms-Burton Bill last year to
isolate Cuba by preventing foreigners investing in the Caribbean
country.
</P>
<P>
The bill would allow Americans to sue in U.S. courts foreign
companies deemed to have profited from investments in property
confiscated by Havana.
</P>
<P>
But the EU, along with other main trading partners of the
U.S. protested against the bill and threatened to take its
complaint to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said that although the complaint had been suspended,
the EU remains "absolutely resolute" in its opposition to the
unacceptable extraterritorial nature of the Helms-Burton legislation.
</P>
<P>
"It is not acceptable for one country to seek to obtain foreign
policy objective by imposing or threatening to impose sanctions on
what other countries are doing in third countries," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
