<HEADLINE> Second African Oil Trade Conference Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A four-day Second African Oil
Trade Conference started here today, seeking to provide a unique
forum for learning about the latest in oil marketing, risk
management and financing techniques.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Zimbabwean transport and energy minister
Simon Moyo said given the high cost of imports, African
countries, the majority of which are landlocked, were
increasingly facing the problem of ensuring that they offered
fuel at an affordable price.
</P>
<P>
The minister said since a few African countries had oil
resources, a number of logistical problems still militated
against cost effective and satisfactory product distribution on
the world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
He said, "our region depends heavily on petroleum imports and
as such we rely on prices dictated to us by the international
market.
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly this has strengthened our commitment to regional
cooperation through such institutions as COMESA (Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa), SADC (Southern African
Development Community) and indeed the PTA bank (the Eastern and
Southern African Trade and Development bank) itself," said Moyo.
</P>
<P>
The conference was organised by the PTA bank, the African
export import bank, Citibank, Nigeria National Petroleum
Corporation, Shell International, Gulf Africa Petroleum
Corporation and Zimbabwe Banking Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The conference is a follow up to last year's conference which
was also held in Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
