<HEADLINE> Greece: Position to Recall Envoy in Iran Not Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government reaffirmed
today that there had been no change concerning the issue of
recalling its ambassador from Iran following a European Union (EU)
Presidency request that all EU member-states should do so.
</P>
<P>
The Eu call came after a German court accused Iranian political
leaders of ordering the assassination of exiled Kurdish dissidents
in the German capital city of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Greece, the only EU country not to recall its envoy from
Tehran, was continuing to examine the issue "in its details" in
order "to see how it will handle" the matter, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
Late last week, Greece voiced reservations over the EU request,
saying "the isolation of a country in order to help it be
incorporated in an international system is not the best way," and
"we are examining the whole issue."
</P>
<P>
Bonn immediately reacted with the German Foreign Ministry
expressing "surprise" at Athens' stance and warning that such a
move refused the " European solidarity towards Germany."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the German reaction, Reppas today stressed that
there was "solidarity" with Germany, but there was "no antagonism"
with Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
