<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls for Cease-fire in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday again called for cease-fire in Zaire after
learning that the government and rebel force had accepted a
U.N.five-point peace plan.
</P>
<P>
"While I am pleased that the parties to the conflict in Zaire
have accepted the five-point peace plan endorsed by the Security
Council, I am concerned that its implementation has not yet began
in earnest," Annan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Saying he was encouraged that President Mobutu had agreed to a
dialogue, Annan appealed to all member states to press Kabila,
leader of the advancing rebel force, and his supporters to seek a
negotiated solution through a cease-fire and sustained talks on
the future of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"A durable solution cannot be achieved through military means,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Annan also called for concerted international efforts in
bringing a peaceful solution of the Zaire conflict.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that Zaire is on the verge of major political
change," he said. "but this change has to be managed, with the
support of the international community, in a concerted and focused
manner."
</P>
<P>
"The stakes are high," he said. "If we are successful, Zaire
could begin to move in the direction of national reconciliation,
democracy and prosperity. If we fail, it will mean misery and
stagnation for millions of people in the region."
</P>
</TEXT>
