<HEADLINE> Feature: Refugees in Eastern Zaire in Bitterness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KISANGANI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- It is the general hope of some
75,000 refugees in the Kasese camp, eastern Zaire, to end their
exodus, return home and live a peaceful life.
</P>
<P>
About 100 to 200 refugees die every day in the camp, located
in bushes 26 kilometers south of Kisangani, the third largest
city in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Cholera and other infectious diseases are seen among the
refugees, most of them Hutus fleeing Rwanda during the 1994
genocide and traveling over 1,000 kilometers to the Kisangani
region.
</P>
<P>
Mukakabanda Beata, 11, wanders in the camp every day with her
5-month-old brother on her back. When asked where are her
parents, Beata cried,"I am missing mama and papa."
</P>
<P>
Beata and her brother are now taken care of by her mother's
sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
Nkerabahizi Donatien from Burundi also missed his parents and
came to Zaire with his younger brother and sister. He even does
not know if his parents are still alive.
</P>
<P>
There are no newspapers or radios in the camp, leaving no
means for the refugees to get to know what has happened in their
home countries. Many refugees said what they can hope is just
that things will get better.
</P>
<P>
Once security in their home countries gets restored, they will
return, the refugees repeated.
</P>
<P>
"I like my country. The Hutus and Tutsis should be brothers.
They should not kill each other. Once I get to know there is
security in my country, I will return there to make some
contribution to national development," said Furuha Soidi, a
refugee in the camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
