<HEADLINE> Southern African Irrigation Workshop Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A three-day southern African
irrigation technology transfer workshop in support of food
security started here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening the workshop, Zimbabwean agriculture minister Dennis
Norman said southern African countries need sound investment in
water harvesting and irrigation infrastructure for the region to
reduce the variability of agricultural production and ensure food
security.
</P>
<P>
He said recurrent droughts and uneven distribution of rainfall
were serious constraints to agricultural production and food
security in many African countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed good government policies were required for
establishing a conducive environment for the participation of
smallholder farmers and well-trained farmers and personnel with
adequate technical knowledge required for the implementation and
monitoring of various irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was jointly organised by the U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organisation (FAO) and the International Programme
for Technology Research in Irrigation and Drainage (IPTRID) of
the world bank.
</P>
<P>
The participants will look at ways of reducing the cost and
improving access to irrigation technologies for individual
farmers or smallholder farmer groups, the promotion of local
manufacture and demonstration of irrigation equipment and
provision of technical services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
