<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Minister Rules Out Contamination of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean agriculture minister
Dennis Norman today ruled out any possibility of the country's
tobacco being affected by the blue mould disease, saying the
disease does not occur in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said it was impossible for Zimbabwean tobacco to have been
affected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
"It does not exist here nor this part of the world but in
north and south America, Europe, Australia and the Mediterranean
regions," said Norman.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, relevant authorities would soon launch their
own investigations into the matter.
</P>
<P>
The disease is said to cause substantial damage to seedlings
in nurseries and to tobacco in the field. In countries where it
is endemic, it is controlled by means of very expensive
fungicides.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the world's third largest exporter of tobacco,
with the crop being the country's single largest foreign currency
earner, bringing into the country 636 million U.S. dollars last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
