<HEADLINE> AL Chief Urges Somali Factions to Reconcile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid said here today the league is exerting strenuous
efforts to push all Somali factions to attend the National
Reconciliation Conference scheduled to be held in June.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a meeting with Somalia National
Alliance leader Hussein Farah Aideed today.
</P>
<P>
Meguid reiterated that the league will maintain dialog with
different factions in Somali in order to reach a settlement for
the crisis acceptable to all.
</P>
<P>
As part of the recent Egyptian consultations with various
Somali factions, President Hosni Mubarak today also held talks
with Aideed on rebuilding Somalia and the reconciliation process
initiated by the transitional government since March.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said after meeting the
visiting Somali leader Sunday that "it is vital for Somali leaders
to find common ground for ending the problems in the country."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Somali faction leader said he has appealed for
"moral" and "regional" support from Egypt to help resume
contacts with neighboring countries and restore stability.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, leader of the most powerful militia in the southern
half of the Somali capital, Mogadishu, arrived here Friday.
</P>
<P>
His visit followed the one paid last month by his rivals in the
Somali National Salvation Council, an umbrella group representing
26 factions fighting him.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of Mogadishu's
northern section, also came here to meet Egyptian officials
mediating in the six-year Somali conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 ouster of the late President Mohamed Siad Barre,
Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by factional
leaders, who continued to fight to expand their turfs despite
several peace conferences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
