<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proceeds from Oil-for-Food Plan Exceed $1 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Proceeds from the
oil-for-food plan, a program to alleviate the severe humanitarian
situation in Iraq, have exceeded one billion dollars so far, a UN
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the news briefing, Juan Carlos Brandt, associate
spokesman for UN secretary-general, said that funds deposited and
distributed came to 1,046 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
UN Department of Humanitarian Affairs reported that Iraqi side
has submitted 48 oil contracts and all of them have been approved,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 468 goods applications have been submitted to UN
Secretariat and 124 goods applications submitted to the sanctions
committee.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has imposed strict economic sanctions
against Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait in August 1990. To
alleviate the severe sanctions impact, the UN Security Council
adopted resolution 986 in April 1995, allowing Iraq to export oil
worth two billion dollars in six months. The UN Secretary-General
approved implementation of the oil-for-food plan in December 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
