<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Takes Tough Line on Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
has vowed to block the reform process of the European Union (EU)
at the Inter-Governmental Conference (IGC) unless Britain's EU
partners agree to reform the bloc's fishing policies.
</P>
<P>
Major, whose ruling Conservative Party is lagging behind the
opposition Labor Party by some 18 percentage points, was taking a
firmer line on relations with the EU in a bid to win back more
votes in the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an election campaign rally in the fishing port of
Newlyn of southwest England today, Major said he was prepared to
veto the EU's long-running IGC conference when it concludes in
Amsterdam in June.
</P>
<P>
"The IGC won't come to a successful conclusion until... the
problem of quota-hopping is resolved satisfactorily and it cannot
come to a solution without unanimity," Major said.
</P>
<P>
Major warned last year that he would block the IGC, crucial to
EU's plans to expand from 15 members to more than 20 in the coming
decade, if it did not solve the quota-hopping issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
