<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries urged to Make Use of Medicinal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan official today called
on African countries to make use of medicinal plants to produce
value added products for higher earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Environment and
Natural Resources, William Mayaka, was opening here today a
regional workshop on medicinal plants and herbal medicine in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that at least 7,000 medicinal compounds used in
the West to manufacture medicines are derived from plants
originating from the tropical countries, particularly from
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official noted that the pharmaceutical industry in
the West based on plant compounds generate an average 320 billion
U.S. Dollars every year.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, this amount of money has not had any impact
on economies of the African countries from which many medicinal
plants originate.
</P>
<P>
He urged African countries to put more investment in research
into new uses of their medicinal plants and into the ways of
obtaining value added products.
</P>
<P>
The workshop organized by OAU Scientific, Technological and
Research Commission is scheduled to discuss policy issues
regarding access, ownership and conservation of medicinal plants
and herbal medicine in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Attending the workshop were representatives from Nigeria,
Cameroon, Madagascar, Uganda, Tanzania, South Africa, Malawi,
Ethiopia and Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
