<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Threaten to Seize German Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian students warned here
today that they would seize the German Embassy unless the German
government make a formal apology to the Iranian nation and
retreat from hostility against Iran.
</P>
<P>
The move is the harshest reaction from the Iranian students
since the announcement of the ruling of the Berlin court last
Thursday which charged Iran's top political leaders with ordering
the assassination of four Kurdish opposition leaders in Berlin's
Mykonos restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that hundreds of
university students staged the anti-German demonstration in front
of the German Embassy this afternoon. The law enforcement forces
had cordoned off the embassy and Ferdowsi street where the
embassy is located.
</P>
<P>
The report said the special guards protecting the German
embassy in Tehran arrested some of the students who attempted to
break into the security line of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
Police had cordoned off the whole Ferdowsi street leading to
the embassy. The demonstration caused traffic jam in the streets
near the embassy where police prevented the protesters from
reaching the embassy compound, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The students chanting slogans urged the German government to
make formal apology to Iran for "the blunder perpetrated by a
German court against Iran."
</P>
<P>
This was the third demonstration held by Iranians within a
week in the wake of the ruling of the Berlin court regarding to
the Mykonos case.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Iran launched a nationwide anti-German wave with
tens of thousands of people turning out here to protest the
Berlin court verdict.
</P>
<P>
Similar demonstrations were also held in 12 Iranian cities,
including Qom, Shiraz and Tabriz.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators urged the Iranian government to sever diplomatic
relations and economic ties between Bonn and Tehran, to
prosecute German firms which provide chemical weapons to Iraq
during the Iranian-Iraqi war between 1980 and 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
