<HEADLINE> ACP States Urged to Promote Regional Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 14 (Xinhua) -- African, Caribbean and Pacific
(ACP) countries should intensify efforts to promote regional
trade and the private sector in their economic development, a
Zimbabwean business figure said today.
</P>
<P>
Danny Meyer, the president of the Federation of ACP Chambers
of commerce, industry and other economic operations, urged ACP
countries to accelerate economic and social development so as to
meet the mounting global challenges.
</P>
<P>
Meyer, also the president of the Zimbabwean National Chamber
of Commerce, has just returned from a major conference of the ACP
Chambers of Commerce in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference reaffirmed the need to further support
private sector participation in developing, diversifying and
increasing trade among ACP member states.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, delegates discussed future ACP/European
Union relations after the expiry of the Lome IV Convention in
2000.
</P>
<P>
Meyer said the so-called green paper by the European
Commission on post-Lome IV relations recognized the need for ACP
states to accelerate their economic growth and social development
in a competitive global environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
