<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Special Envoy for Cyprus to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. special envoy on Cyprus Han
Sung Joo officially announced here today that he will step down
from his post at the end of his term in office on April 30.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Han, who arrived here
Saturday on his final trip to the island as U.N. special envoy,
said that due to the growing level of intensity of efforts aimed
at bringing together the leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities, it would be better to have someone who would devote
"more time, more presence and would be more involved" in the
ongoing effort.
</P>
<P>
However, Han, the former foreign minister of Republic of
Korea, declined to specify who will be his successor.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed as U.N. Secretary-General's special
representative for Cyprus to replace former Canadian prime
minister Joe Clark in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Han cited his other responsibilities and the distance between
Cyprus and Seoul as difficulties that impede his task as special
representative.
</P>
<P>
"I have told the Secretary-General that I do not wish to be
considered for an extension once my initial period of
appointment is completed at the end of April," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Coming from a divided country myself, I do not underestimate
the delicate complexities involved in trying to balance both
internal and external pressures and interests," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy called on Cypriots of both communities to
provide their leaders with the support and encouragement they
need to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
Han said both community leaders have "love and devotion" to
their respective communities. He expressed the hope that this
will translate into a negotiated settlement that will benefit
both communities by ensuring security, equality and prosperity
for all Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Han's current visit followed a meeting between U.N. Chief Kofi
Annan and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in Geneva last
week.
</P>
<P>
Han is expected to meet Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and
Denktash as part of the ongoing U.N.-sponsored proximity talks,
aimed at getting the two veteran leaders to negotiating table
for face-to-face talks on solving the protracted Cyprus problem,
which has remained unsolved for the past 23 years.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the 37 percent of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
