<HEADLINE> Botswana to Depreciate National Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Botswana will depreciate
its currency Pula to offset problems likely to affect its
national economy, Southern African Broadcasting Association
(SABA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
A strong Pula would have had an adverse effect on Botswana's
economy and led to increased unemployment, SABA quoted Botswanan
Vice-President and Finance Minister Festus Mogae as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mogae said although the decision to let Pula slip against
South African currency Rand has put Botswana-based importers at a
disadvantage, the overall result will be positive to the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Currently the exchange rate of Pula against Rand is about
0.7810 to one.
</P>
<P>
Mogae said Botswana's foreign reserves are kept in the central
banks of 18 countries, including Britain, the Netherlands, Japan,
South Africa and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
