<HEADLINE> Chirac Wishes Partnership Between NATO, Baltic States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today told visiting Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis that the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) could envisage a
``partnership of security'' with its candidate countries which
cannot join it in the first wave, such as the Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Madrid summit to be held in July will decide which
countries can join it in the first wave in 1999. Hungary, Poland,
the Czech Republic and, as France wishes, probably Romania, will
be admitted in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
The French presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said that
Baltic and other eastern European countries which wish to join the
NATO can reinforce their relations with NATO, the European Union,
the Western European Union and Scandinavian countries through
signing such a partnership of security.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also raised the idea of establishing a charter between
the NATO and five non-NATO Baltic states: Latvia, Lithuania,
Estonia, Finland and Sweden, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The Latvian president, who is on a state visit here until
Wednesday, expressed his wish that the security concern of the
three former Soviet Baltic states should be taken into account and
their candidacy not be turned down by NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
