<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sets Tough Rules for State Tenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has adopted
strict measures for state tenders as part of government's bid to
generate economic benefits for the local economy, said a source
here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the National Industrial Participation Program, all local
companies tendering for state contracts with an imported content
exceeding 10 million U.S. Dollars, like their overseas
counterparts, should be required to set up a separate business.
</P>
<P>
The program, drawn up by the Department of Trade and Industry
(DTI), has been criticized by some business communities for lack
of consultation with concerned role-players, said the source.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa's main business bodies, including the
South African Chamber of Business and the Foundation for African
Business and Consumer Services, do not yet formally respond to
the program, the source added.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the program, winners of state tenders, at all
governmental and parastatal levels, must start projects which are
economically viable as part of a bid to increase jobs, exports
and investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The winners should also help encourage technology transfer,
accelerate affirmative action and the development of small
business.
</P>
<P>
Vassie Ponsamy, a DTI director in charge of the program, said
the program should be used at the imported content level and as a
benchmark.
</P>
<P>
Ponsamy admitted the government could have consulted business
more meaningfully at the National Economic, Development and
Labour Council before the formal presentation of the program.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed claims that the program would raise the cost of
state tenders, adding normal competitive bidding would instead
bring down the price significantly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
