<HEADLINE> Horticultural Industry Code Launched in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Horticultural Crops
Development Authority today launched a code of conduct for the
industry to enhance its reputation on the world market.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here today said that the code is
designed to serve as a guideline for both the buyer and seller of
fresh horticultural produce in the country.
</P>
<P>
The code will also act as a framework to the development of
legally binding contract to be executed by the buyer and seller.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony, the Director of Agriculture, T.K.
Tuei, called on both producers and buyers to stick to agreed
obligations for the benefit of the horticultural industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that last year fresh produce exports grew by 18
percent to 84,824 tons, earning for the country about 120 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The industry has been growing rapidly in the eastern African
country in the last two decades, registering constant growth
rates of between 10 to 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The industry is now the fourth biggest foreign exchange earner
after tourism, tea and coffee in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Tuei noted that there was need to encourage responsible
production and marketing practices to ensure produce quality and
meet the international market demands including social and
environmental aspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
