<HEADLINE> More Emergency Relief Supplies Donated For Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government
has donated emergency relief supplies worth 119,000 US dollars
for flood victims in Lindi Region, eastern Tanzania, a staement
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement released by the Tanzania Information Services
here today indicated that the supplies consists of 50 tents, 864
sleeping mats, two rolls of plastic sheet, 1,200 blankets and
medicine and medical kit for 10,000 people for three months.
</P>
<P>
Last week the United Nations Department of Humanitarian
Affairs (DHA) provided an emergency grant of 20,000 US dollars to
Tanzania to meet immediate needs for Kilwa District in Lindi
Region flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Chilldren's Fund (UNICEF) also offered 12
tones of emergency food and medical supplies worth 45,800 US
dollars from its emergency stocks in Ngara for the flood victims
in Lindi Region.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Resident
Representative, Mr. Victor Angelo handed over the first
consignment of the supplies to the Lindi Regional Commissioner,
Mr. Abubakar Mgumia at Kilwa air strip last week.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Red Cross Society was the first to lift its
supplies to the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 50,000 people in Kilwa District have
been affected by the recent floods which killed over 50 people,
left more than 2,100 people homeless and washed away over 4,000
hectares of food crops plantations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
