<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Launches Intensive Peace Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will send a top envoy to
Washington Tuesday in a move to step up its diplomatic campaign
to restart the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, President Hosni Mubarak's political advisor, will
head for Washington for talks with Dennis Ross, U.S. Mideast Peace
Coordinator, on U.S.-European proposals aimed at pushing forward
Arab-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Baz will present
Egypt's ideas to the United States since the Egyptian side has been
updated on the European and U.S. proposals in general.
</P>
<P>
"Baz will fully explain that Egyptian stand within the
framework of its well-known lines," Moussa told reporters
following a meeting between Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit came as the separate initiatives proposed by the
U.S. and the EU to revive Israeli-Palestinian talks had flopped.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the intensive diplomatic drive launched by Egypt to
revive the Mideast peace process, Moussa pointed to "three focal
points."
</P>
<P>
He mentioned Jerusalem and the construction of settlements in
the occupied Arab lands, implementation of Oslo agreements, with
particular focus on redeployment, and resumption of peace talks,
which he called "the core of the matter."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian diplomatic move followed the attempts by U.S. and
EU to discourage Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu from a
controversial Jewish housing project in East Jerusalem, a condition
the Palestinians insist for resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu rejects any link between Palestinian attempts to halt
violence and Israeli settlement policies and vows to press ahead
with the construction of the Har Homa neighborhood, a move that
has stranded the peace talks and sparked daily clashes in West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of Arafat's visit to Cairo, Mubarak said
U.S. President Bill Clinton had asked him to send a top envoy to
meet with U.S. officials on means of breaking the peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the Palestinians are ready for negotiations,
provided that the negotiating process be balanced.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. peace initiative demands a halt of the Har
Homa settlement, Moussa said: "I am not in a position to speak
about the initiative but I hope that any initiative would include
this (settlement freeze)."
</P>
<P>
Moussa emphasized no peace initiative may proceed without
touching on the question of Jerusalem and Jewish settlements,
maintaining that peace talks should resume on the basis of the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed reports to the effect that arrangements are
under way for an Arab summit following the greater Bairam,
an annual holy occasion for Muslims.
</P>
<P>
He said the statement of last year's Cairo Arab summit, the
first plenary top-level Arab meeting in six years, are in effect.
</P>
<P>
However, Moussa said it is possible to conduct swift
consultations and adopt suitable decisions among the Arab
countries in the current Mideast peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Arafat would fly to Valletta, Malta to attend the
Euro-Mediterranean conference where he will meet with Ross and
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
