<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Arabia Extends No Invitation to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has not yet
extended an invitation to Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani for a state visit, a senior Saudi diplomat said
here tonight in contradiction with a previous statement by the
Iranian side.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Ambassador to Iran Abdullatif Abdullah Al-Maimanee told
Xinhua that President Rafsanjani will not pay a visit to Saudi
Arabia during the hajj pilgrimage. He also said that the Iranian
president will "definitely" not go to Saudi Arabia in April.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, President Rafsanjani does not need an
invitation if he goes to Saudi Arabia during the hajj pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
"All Muslims can go to Mecca. That is the invitation extended
by God. It is the same to Rafsanjani," he added.
</P>
<P>
What the senior Saudi diplomat said contradicts a statement made
by Iranian Ambassador to Riyadh Nouri Shahroodi, who claimed early
this month that Iranian President Rafsanjani would go to Saudi
Arabia during hajj pilgrimage in April.
</P>
<P>
Some Iranian official sources said that Rafsanjani would
go to Saudi Arabia after the 7th presidential elections --
maybe in June.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi ambassador said: "That is what they are
talking about. As for me, I have heard no information of the
visit by President Rafsanjani to Saudi Arabia either from my
country or from the Iranian government."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian media made a large publicity campaign about the
visit by President Rafsanjani to Saudi Arabia, claiming that a
chapter is forthcoming to enhance the relations between the two
giants in the Persian Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said in
a press conference on April 9 that the timetable had not yet been
set for the visit by Rafsanjani to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
But, he noted that Rafsanjani was invited to make an official
visit to Saudi Arabia during his meeting with Saudi Prince
Abdullah on the sideline of a conference of the Organization of
Islamic Countries (OIC) in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Some Iranian sources said that Rafsanjani could not go to
Saudi Arabia because he is now fully occupied with domestic
affairs, especially the State Expediency Council which is
headed by Rafsanjani himself.
</P>
<P>
But, some observers here noted that the reason for Saudi
King Fahd not to extend the official invitation to Rafsanjani is
due pressure from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi king would not like to take the risk of offending
U.S. President Bill Clinton by inviting the enemy of the United
States, which still accuses Iran of involvement in an explosion of
the U.S. military complex in Saudi Arabia last year.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab diplomats said that the Saudi king made a cold
response even to an invitation extended by Iranian President
Rafsanjani to attend an OIC summit scheduled in Tehran in
December.
</P>
<P>
The king only welcomed the invitation, but he did not
promise his visit to Tehran at that time.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that Iran is trying its best to improve
relations with Persian Gulf countries, especially Saudi Arabia, in
a bid to confront the military threat by the United States
and the international isolation.
</P>
<P>
But it would be very difficult for the Arab countries in the
Gulf to make a big stride in improving their relations with Iran
since they are still distrusting Tehran and accusing it of
interfering with the internal affairs of the Gulf countries and
exporting Islamic revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
