<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Warring Parties in Zaire to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim today urged
Zaire's warring parties to end fighting and engage in
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, he said OAU wishes Zaire crisis be
resolved as soon as possible, adding that OAU will offer support
to any efforts concerned.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that the second round of talks on Zaire
to be held in South Africa this week would bear fruits in
restoring peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks on Zaire's peace was held in South
Africa last week.
</P>
<P>
However, Salim stressed that the decision on whom to lead the
central African country would be made by the people of Zaire and
not anybody else.
</P>
<P>
"Let the people decide who they want through elections and let
us respect their choice," he said, adding that there should be a
ceasefire first so as to allow peaceful and democratic
transition.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, Zaire's rebels led by
Laurent Kabila gave Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko the
deadline of last Sunday to signal his intention of stepping down.
</P>
<P>
Salim said he personally followed President Mobutu in France
last December and advised him to go back home and negotiate with
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said he also sent an OAU representative to deliver the same
suggestion to Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is united democratic Zaire, because if we have a
stable Zaire, South Africa, Southern Africa, West Africa and East
Africa, it will change the outlook of Africa which it is
perceived on other continents as a place where people kill each
other," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim stressed that African problems and crisis will not be
solved by anyone other than the Africans themselves.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the OAU chief appealed to Tanzanians to cultivate
the culture of cooperation and tolerance, saying negotiations are
the best solution to disputes.
</P>
<P>
On the boycott of the House of Representatives sessions by
lawmakers from the opposition party in Zanzibar, he called on the
ruling party and the opposition Civic United Front (CUF) to
discuss the differences instead of boycotting.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the parties to ban their lawmakers from
boycotting the sessions, saying by this way they were doing
injustice to the people who elected them their representatives in
the house.
</P>
<P>
Salim further expressed optimism that the Liberia crisis would
be resolved in the near future and the general elections would be
held next month.
</P>
<P>
Salim said there are also hopes of resolving the conflicts in
Sierra Leone and that efforts were still being made by OAU to
create peace in the horn of Africa, Somalia in particular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
