<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM's Profits Increase 76 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Detroit-based General Motors
Corp. announced today its first-quarter earnings increased 76
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The world's largest automaker said it earned nearly 1.8 billion
U.S. dollars, or 2.30 dollars a share, as compared with the 1.02
billion dollars, or 94 cents a share, in the corresponding period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Revenues totaled 42.26 billion dollars, marking an 8 percent
growth from 39.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
GM's North American Operations automotive unit earned 764
million dollars, as against a 279 million dollars loss in the
first three months of 1996. The profit in the quarter is the
highest level in the operation for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
The growth came even though GM's sales of cars and light trucks
in the first quarter were down 1 percent. GM said its U.S. market
share fell to 30.2 percent from 31.2 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The auto-maker's earnings increase was largely attributed to
the introduction of some 15 new models that are less costly to
produce and reductions in the costs of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
GM's financial arm, General Motors Acceptance Corp., earned 372
million dollars in the recent period, up 20 percent from 309
million dollars a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
