<HEADLINE> Libya Tries to Bring About Rapproachement Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali
Osman Mohammed Taha said here today that the Sudan-Libya-Uganda
meeting held in the Libyan capital of Tripoli Sunday was the
outcome of efforts made by Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi to bring
about rapproachement between the Sudan and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press here today, the Sudanese minister
said that discussions during the meeting focused on adherence to
the charters of the United Nations and the Organization of African
Unity with regard to non-interference with the internal affairs of
others, abstaining from hosting rebel groups and observing the
principles of good neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
Minister Mohammed Taha added that the Sudanese side briefed the
participants on the latest developments of the peace process in the
Sudan and the peace agreement to be signed on April 21 between the
Sudanese government and a number of southern Sudanese rebel
factions.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that this agreement would have positive
consequences with regard to promoting and stabilizing Sudan's ties
with its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
It was during the visit to Libya by Sudanese President Omar
al-Bashir that Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi contacted the
President of Uganda Yoweri Museveni, requesting the dispatch of a
Ugandan delegation to Tripoli to negotiate with the Sudanese side.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president held a meeting with the Ugandan
delegation in an attempt to play down the tension between the two
countries, which had severed diplomatic ties in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president returned home this morning after a
three-day official visit to Libya which began Friday. He was
seeking Libyan support for the Sudanese government to cope
with Sudan's internal problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
