<HEADLINE> UN Special Envoy for Cyprus Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan had accepted the resignation of Han Sung-Joo from the
special representative of the UN secretary-general for Cyprus, a
UN spokesman announced today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard said that Han Sung-Joo had informed
Secretary-General Kofi Annan that due to other pressing
commitments, he would not be able to continue in that position
beyond the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general has accepted Professor Han's decision
with much regret and expressed his warm appreciation for the
dedicated work he has carried out in the last 12 months within the
framework of the secretary-general's mission of good offices," he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Han Sung-Joo was foreign minister of the Republic of Korea from
February 1993 to December 1994. He was professor of political
science and president of the Ilmin International Relations
Institute at Korea University. He had also held a variety of
academic positions at different universities and research
institutions in Korea and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the UN secretary-general would
engage in early consultations to identify a successor to Han
Sung-Joo so as to bring about a comprehensive settlement in
Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
