<HEADLINE> Kinkel: Poland Will Be in First Wave to Join EU, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today assured that Germany is and will continue to be a reliable
advocate of Poland being one of the first candidates to join the
European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
Addressing a German-Polish forum in Bonn, Kinkel also stressed
that the guideline for the integration of Poland as well as the
Czech Republic, Hungary and other eastern European countries is a
swift adjustment of their political and economic general
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Some countries would make the grade soon while others would
still need some time, Kinkel said, adding that for the latter the
EU should make sure that they will be able to catch up quickly.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister also stressed that the opening of
the EU and the NATO should not be allowed to lead to new rifts in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Given Russia's weight and importance, it must be treated
equally during the integration process, Kinkel said, adding that
the security and stability in Europe are unimaginable without
Russia.
</P>
<P>
But he called on Moscow to speak out against the Cold-War-style
"demonization" of NATO during public debates, saying that this
also belongs to confidence-building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
