<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Led by technology shares, stocks
on Wall Street rebounded today from a steep drop of Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 60.21 points to
6,451.90. It was bolstered by some strong first-quarter profit
reports. The Dow, which traded at a modest loss for much of the
session, slid nearly 150 points Friday to wipe out the rest of
what had been a 10 percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow struggled much of the day despite better-than-expected
earnings reports from Coca-Cola, Travelers Group, and General
Motors.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where its volume totaled 406.78
million shares down from 440.48 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Most major measures also turned positive in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 6.08 to 743.73, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 2.02 to 391.49.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.51 to 1,216.41, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.16 to 52.97.
</P>
<P>
There were no major economic reports today to calm or aggravate
the inflation worries that have dragged the markets lower over the
past month.
</P>
<P>
Fed officials have warned that the central bank will raise
interest rates aggressively to slow the pace of borrowing and
spending. That would help ease inflationary pressures, but could
cut into company profits in the process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
