<HEADLINE> US Envoy to Go to Mideast for Peace Revival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright announced today that she will send U.S. mediator Dennis
Ross to the Middle East this week in an attempt to revive the
stalled peace talks between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after Albright held a telephone talk
over the weekend with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, which was
described by State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns as "a good
round of discussions."
</P>
<P>
Ross' mission, Albright said, was aimed to get Israel and the
Palestinians to drop their conditions and resume negotiations,
which have stalled for several weeks as a result of Israel's
decision to build Jewish homes in traditionally Arab east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ross will consult separately with Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on "how to stem the violence and on
what steps they are prepared to take to stop the deterioration and
lay the basis for making the peace process work again," Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state said she did not know whether the two
sides were prepared to take that step. But a decision will be made
on what to do next when Ross returns back from his Mideast trip
with assessment of the situation there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
