<HEADLINE> Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The new Sino-U.S. textile
agreement is good news for Hong Kong's textile industry, as it
provides for the smooth continuation of bilateral trade relations
between the two countries, says Hong Kong Trade Development
Council's latest Trade Watch report.
</P>
<P>
The four-year agreement, which was signed between China and the
U.S. on February 2 this year after months of negotiations,
replaced the 1992 accord which expired on December 31 last year.
</P>
<P>
It contains four major changes in the previous one. There were
changes in China's quotas for 50 categories or subcategories.
Provisions were made for adjusting China's quotas after it becomes
a member of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The report points out that the changes in China's quotas will
have an effect on Hong Kong since many Hong Kong companies operate
production facilities in southern China.
</P>
<P>
For highly utilized categories where the quotas were increased,
Hong Kong can anticipate improved re-export levels in 1997. For
categories where the quotas were reduced, by and large there will
be little impact on trade flows as few were highly utilized, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the quota changes, the new agreement will provide new
trade opportunities as well as challenges for Hong Kong's
companies, the report says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Welcomes Arrival of Multinational Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government today
hailed the arrival of the Italian-led multinational force which is
to protect humanitarian relief operations and help stabilize the
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Albania's Prime Minister Bashkim Fino welcomed the arrival,
saying the force will help restore peace and order to the country
which has been gripped by violence and unrest over the last two
months.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Albania extends its best thanks in the
name of the Albanian people for the readiness they have
demonstrated in helping us at this delicate time," Fino said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,200 Italian, French and Spanish soldiers landed in
Albania today and fanned out across the country to take control of
harbors, airports and other main communication facilities after
weeks of violence.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government promised to carry out constructive and
close cooperation with the multinational force approved by the
United Nations late last month.
</P>
<P>
The Italian-led eight-nation force on the mission called
"Operation Alba" will have the right to defend themselves,
although they are not authorized to disarm Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Albania is awash with guns since people looted weapons
following unrest caused by the collapse of fraudulent savings
schemes in January.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people have been killed in the past months of
near-anarchy and much of southern Albania is still under the
control of armed protesters who insist that President Sali
Berisha resign over the collapse of the savings schemes in which
thousands of Albanian families lost their savings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
