<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, U.S. Sign Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and the United States
signed two agreements here today, one on mutual legal assistance
in criminal matters and the other on the transfer of sentenced
persons.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on the Transfer of Sentenced Persons (TSP
Agreement) is the first agreement which Hong Kong has signed on
international cooperation in the enforcement of penal sentences.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Mutual Legal Assistance in Criminal Matters
(MLA) Agreement) is the second agreement which Hong Kong has
signed on international cooperation against crime. The first was
signed with Australia in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
The main aspects of the assistance stipulated by the MLA
agreement include taking evidence, searching for and seizing items
which are relevant to criminal matters, producing documentary
evidence relevant to the criminal matters, transferring persons
(including prisoners) between the Hong Kong and the US
jurisdiction, confiscating the proceeds of crime and serving
documents.
</P>
<P>
The TSP Agreement contains essential safeguards which are
normally found in agreements governing the transfer of sentenced
persons. They include: the conduct in respect of which the
sentenced person is imprisoned must be criminal in both
jurisdictions and any adjustment to the sentence by the sending
jurisdiction must be executed by the receiving jurisdiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
