<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import Yellow Corn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will import
350,000 tons of yellow corn with 35 percent preferential tariff to
ease a corn shortage in the country, a senior food official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Joemari Gerochi, head of the National Food Authority (NFA),
said the country's food producers had earlier asked the authority
to approve the importation of 400,000 tons of yellow corn to meet
an estimated corn shortage of 800,000 tons this year.
</P>
<P>
But he said the NFA limited the requested imports to 350,000
tons to prevent competition with local production.
</P>
<P>
The planned imports will come from the United States and
Argentina, according to Gerochi.
</P>
<P>
But the corn import volume has yet to be endorsed by the
cabinet, the president and finally the congress.
</P>
<P>
The NFA will hold talks with the United States and Argentine
this month to ensure that the imports will all come in by June,
one month before corn harvest starts in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to Gerochi, half of the 350,000 tons of corn imports
will be allocated to hog and poultry farmers while the other half
will be bid out to allow those with small allocations to have
additional supply to meet their corn requirements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
