<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Population Grows 5.7 Percent in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada had a population of
28,846,761 on May 14, 1996, when the latest census was conducted,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
International migration and natural increase added more than
1.5 million or 5.7 percent to Canada's population over the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
Canada's population has doubled in 45 years from just over 14
million in 1951, the federal agency said in the release of the
first data from the 1996 census. Other data will be released over
the next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Canada's rate of population growth slowed between 1991
and 1996, compared to the previous five-year period, which saw a
growth rate of 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Yet, compared to the rest of the industrialized world, Canada
is still a front-runner. Its population grew at an annual average
rate of 1.1 percent, the highest of all G-7 industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
Average annual increases for the rest of G-7 countries varied
from 0.1 percent for Italy to 1.0 percent for the United States.
</P>
<P>
The overall number of people on the planet rose at an annual
growth rate of 1.5 percent between 1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Canada accounts for about 0.5 percent of the global
population.
</P>
<P>
The census also showed that every province and territory,
except Newfoundland, recorded an increase in population over the
past five years. British Columbia recorded by far the highest
growth rate of 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The agency noted that the 1996 census confirmed a trend seen
for a number of years showing the distribution of Canada's
population shifting from east to west.
</P>
<P>
In 1951, 15 percent of Canada's population lived in Alberta and
British Columbia. By 1996, that had increased to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Ontario's share of the population has increased from
33 percent in 1951 to 37 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Over this 45-year period, the Atlantic Provinces' proportion
has fallen from 12 percent to the current eight percent, while the
population in Quebec has declined from 29 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Manitoba's share of the population declined
from six percent in 1951 to four percent in 1996. Saskatchewan's
dropped from six percent to three percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Launches "Buy Russian" Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today called on Russians to buy Russian-made products in order to
help ailing national industries.
</P>
<P>
In a radio address Yeltsin stated that his appeal is
buttressed by higher quality of goods produced in the country as
a result of honest competition.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin said the support for Russian products would not
pose a threat to foreign imports. "There should be no concern that
I am going to ban foreign products on the Russian
market. Absolutely not. Honest competition must reign in Russia,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said "I want our people to give preference to
Russian-made products, wear costumes and shoes made in Russian
factories and buy Russian-made refrigerators and furniture".
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin meanwhile said that it was not mean there to be a tough
protectionism to ban foreign goods from the Russian market, but
"Russian-made goods should excel in quality."
</P>
<P>
In the radio address, Yeltsin also ordered officials to buy
Russian-made cars.
</P>
<P>
Citing an example in Russian defense products which many
foreign countries are willing to buy, Yeltsin said that far
from all goods made overseas were quite good and drew attention
to insufficient advertising of national products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
