<HEADLINE> Canadian Cities Get Bigger, Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- With the country's population
reaching 28,846,761 last May, the biggest Canadian cities are
getting much bigger, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The latest census, conducted on May 14, 1996, showed 17,864,646
Canadians live in the 25 census metropolitan areas, which
represents an increase of 6.4 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 36.2 percent of the population lived in the four
most populous metropolitan areas of Toronto, Montreal, Vancouver
and Ottawa-Hull.
</P>
<P>
With a total of 4,263,757 people, Toronto has become the first
Canadian city with more than four million people, the federal
agency said in the release of the first data from the 1996 census.
Other data will be released over the next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Montreal and Vancouver remain the second and third largest
cities in Canada, with population growing at a rate of 3.7 percent
and 14.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
As the fourth largest, the Ottawa-Hull metropolitan area saw
its population rose 7.3 percent over the previous census, passing
the one million level for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The fifth to 10th largest cities in Canada are respectively
Edmonton, Calgary, Quebec, Winnipeg, Hamilton and London, with a
population from 862,597 to 398,616. 
</P>
</TEXT>
