<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Welcome China's Policy on HK Residents' Nationality, Right of Abode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nearly all the local newspapers
published commentaries here today, highly appraising China's
policy on Hong Kong residents' nationality and right of abode.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of
China's State Council on Sunday in Beijing gave a detailed account
of the policies regarding Hong Kong residents' nationality and
right of abode issues.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers praised these policies as clear, generous and
practicable, saying they took into full consideration Hong Kong
people's interests and will no doubt alleviate the worries of
those living in the territory and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the newspapers pointed out that the nationality and
right of abode issues are internal affairs of China, and related
legislative work should be up to the Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC), the legislative arm of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The commentary carried by Wen Wei Po said the policies show
flexibility when implementing China's Nationality Law in Hong
Kong, and provide a chance for emigrants to participate in the
cause of bettering Hong Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily noted in an editorial that the
Chinese government has solicited advice and opinions from Hong
Kong people in laying out the policies.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Economic Times said the policies will not only help
maintain Hong Kong people's confidence but also avoid the swarming
home of emigrants on the eve of the handover. They are "good news"
to Hong Kong, it said.
</P>
<P>
Under the policies, Hong Kong emigrants, now living in Canada
and some other countries, can retain their permanent resident
status without giving up foreign nationality if they return to the
territory by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The English-language South China Morning Post and Hong Kong
Standard also gave wide coverage to the policies and reactions
they generated among Hong Kong people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
