<HEADLINE> Hong Kong 1997 Web Site Launched in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong 1997 Web Site,
developed by China Internet, was launched here today to provide
comprehensive information on all the activities and celebrations
associated with Hong Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
The web site includes information in Chinese and English about
the history of Hong Kong, a pictorial history, Hong Kong archives,
the first chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), major events in Hong Kong and a Hong Kong
encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
Editorial content has been contributed by the Xinhua News
Agency, which has provided the web site with a comprehensive
review of Hong Kong -- its past, present and future.
</P>
<P>
A unique section, a pictorial history of Hong Kong, is also
featured, with some historical archive photographs available for
public viewing for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The web site is also a partnership with some of the world's
most prestigious multinational corporations including Oracle, Sun
Microsystems, China Telecom, IBM, Bay Networks, Netscape, Intel,
Mitsubishi Electric, Hong Kong Telecom, Microsoft, Kodak, U.S.
Robotics and Poppe Tyson Interactive.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive and up-to-the minute handover news and photo
service will be featured on the site. It has been planned that
from late June onward, live on-line coverage of key events will be
provided on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony on behalf of the advisors to the Hong
Kong 1997 Web Site, Raymond Ch'ien, member of the HK SAR Executive
Council, said the web site is the result of an international
corporate initiative and is designed to be a gift for Hong Kong
and a recognition of the contributions of all its people.
</P>
<P>
He said it gives the world a comprehensive view of Hong Kong, a
forward-looking, cosmopolitan city that will be world-leading in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong
Kong Branch, and Rita Fan, president of the HK SAR Provisional
Legislative Council, attended the launching ceremony of the web
site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
