<HEADLINE> Nepal to Impose Valued Added Tax Late This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
decided to postpone the implementation of the Value Added Tax
(VAT) system till late this year.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry's VAT Department announced today that the
government will begin to collect the VAT from November 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The decision came out after the local business community voiced
strong opposition to the government's earlier announcement to
impose the VAT from the coming fiscal year starting in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen claimed that the country's economy, tax authorities
and business circles lack adequate preparations for the new tax
regime.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government, in a bid to prevent tax evasion and
increase national revenue, began to prepare for the VAT over two
years ago and it earlier decided to impose the new tax from the
1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The new tax system is expected to help the government double
its annual tax revenue to about 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
