<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stolen Vehicles Handed Back to HK by Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Ten stolen vehicles and one
container were returned today to Hong Kong police by their
counterparts in neighboring Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Returned at Huanggang Border Crossing Point in Shenzhen were
seven saloons, two crane lorries, one heavy goods vehicle and one
40-feet-long container, with a total value of 4.94 million HK
dollars (633,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The vehicles had been reported stolen at various locations in
Hong Kong between February 1992 and August 1996.
</P>
<P>
The return is the 16th of its kind since the Guangdong Public
Security Bureau started to hand over recovered vehicles to Hong
Kong police in 1991, bringing the total number of returned private
cars and lorries to 98 and four respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is also the first time a stolen container was returned to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Hong Kong police said today's handing back of
stolen cars symbolized the continual commitment and cooperation
between Hong Kong and the Chinese mainland in combating
cross-border crimes, especially in tackling the problem of
smuggling stolen vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a steady decrease over the past years with a
total of 2,561 cases of missing vehicles recorded last year, a
63-percent drop over 1992," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
