<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Hails Sino-Mauritian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
spoke highly of Sino-Mauritian relations during a meeting with
visiting Mauritian Prime Minister Navin Ramgoolam here today,
hailing Ramgoolam's China tour as of "great significance" to
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Since the two countries established diplomatic relations, Jiang
said, they have carried out fruitful co-operation in various
fields, steadily increased their economic and trade links, and
closely co-operated with and supported each other in international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Some 25 years ago, Ramgoolam's father, then prime minister of
Mauritius, and the first generation of Chinese leadership, forged
diplomatic ties between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that this laid a solid foundation for the development
of friendship between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, he said, China and Mauritius have
increased the exchange of visits between their leaders, enhancing
bilateral friendly relations. While Mauritius has scored
tremendous economic achievements, China has achieved rapid
development in the reform, opening up and the modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
China will resume the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong
Kong in more than two months, the president said, expressing the
belief all these favorable conditions will further stimulate
the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said he is delighted to visit China in celebration of
the 25th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said that his father, as the first prime minister of
Mauritius after its independence, realized China's important
status in the international arena, and decided to forge diplomatic
ties with China.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Mauritius has always been pursuing the "one China"
policy, which, he pledged, will never change in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister expressed his gratitude to China for its
assistance to Mauritius, which has played a significant role in
the economic development of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
During his current visit, he said, the two countries signed an
agreement on the maintenance of a Mauritian honorary consulate
general in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that Hong Kong's return to China will
benefit economic co-operation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang said that China holds that world stability and
development are inseparable from a favorable international and
regional environment.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius has always pursued a foreign policy of neutrality,
peace and non-alliance, actively promoted peace and progress in
Africa, and exerted unremitting efforts to establish a peaceful
region of the Indian Ocean, Jiang said, adding that this
constitutes an important factor for the success of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius, enjoying geographic advantages, wishes to serve as a
bridge between east Asia and Africa, Ramgoolam said, and as the
first presidential country of the Indian Ocean Association for
Regional Co-operation, Mauritius is devoted to the the development
of economic co-operation in the region, and expects China's
participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperation Promising Between Insurers from Taiwan, Hong Kong and inland areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the
insurance industries of China's inland areas, Hong Kong, and
Taiwan say they plan to do more to cultivate cooperation between
the three places, in order to unite the insurance markets for all
Chinese in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The 200 representatives are attending an ongoing insurance
seminar co-sponsored by the Insurance Institute of China and the
Hong Kong Federation of Insurers (HKFI).
</P>
<P>
Wu-Tsung Chen, executive vice president of Cathay Life
Insurance Co., Ltd headquartered in Taipei, said at the seminar
that a strategic alliance is necessary among insurers of the
Taiwan Straits and Hong Kong, and that it will be the first step
toward combining the insurance markets of all Chinese in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, Asia's insurance market has risen to become the top
in the world, an achievement due in part to the combined insurance
market shares of Chinese in these three places, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yongwei, president of the People's Insurance Company of
China(PICC), the country's biggest insurer, said at the seminar's
opening ceremony that the mainland still has great untapped
potential for insurers.
</P>
<P>
"There is bright future to enhance cooperation among the
insurers of Hong Kong, and the two sides of the Straits," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
China, with a 1.2 billion population and a vast insurance
market, generated 75.6 billion yuan in premium income from the
insurance sector last year. The figure will reach 250 billion yuan
by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the mainland insurance market will see double
digit growth rate in the coming years. Recent sample tests show
that nearly half of the urban residents have said they are
considering purchasing life insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
Steven Lau, chairman of HKFI, said that Hong Kong will still
function as a source of advanced knowledge for insurance companies
in the motherland after the handover of Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now has 221 registered insurance companies, which
generated a total premium income of 18.4 billion Hong Kong dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
The tough competition between Hong Kong insurers will continue,
and Hong Kong will maintain a stable growth of premium income this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the possible cooperation among insurers from
the two sides of the Straits and Hong Kong will not only be based
on their shared cultural background, but also Hong Kong's and
Taiwan's similar experiences in rapidly developing the insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
"What is happening in China's inland areas has happened to both
Hong Kong and Taiwan before, which could serve as a 'mirror' for
the opening-up of the insurance industry of the mainland," a Hong
Kong businessmen said.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between the three places in near future will be
based on information-sharing, and Hong Kong will help train the
employees of mainland insurance companies who need it most, said
Dennis J. Pedini, managing director of East Asia Aetna Insurance
Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
