<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Early Reach of Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Health Minister Omid
Medhat Mubarak today called for early reach of medicines in Iraq
under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The minister made this call in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua before attending a scientific lecture here.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Health Minister accused the U.S. of obstructing the
arrival of medicines in Iraq and the approval of contracts for the
purchase of medicines concluded by Iraq with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the UN Sanctions Committee has so far
approved 40 contracts for the purchase of medicines, but the first
batch of these medicines would not arrive in Iraq before the end
of this month or early next month.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Health Minister added that Iraq has submitted to the
UN Sanctions Committee more than 500 contracts for the purchase of
medicines which are badly needed by Iraqi hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food agreement reached between the UN and
Iraq, Iraq has been allowed to export 20 billion dollars of oil in
six months. 30 percent of which will be funneled to the fund for
gulf war reparations and meeting other UN costs. Then Iraq would
have access to about 1.3 billion dollars to purchase food,
medicine and other daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
Food started reaching Iraq on March 20. According to a UN
official, Iraq has since then received 200,000 tonnes of food
articles.
</P>
<P>
So far the UN Sanction Committee has approved 13 out of 90
contracts concluded by Iraq for the purchase of food
articles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
