<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels to Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to hold their
third round of low-level talks on April 23-24 in Cotabato city,
the southern province of Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed today by Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice-chairman
for political affairs, according to the Philippine News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming technical committee meeting will discuss
matters regarding the implementation of a local cease-fire
agreement and the positioning of combatants in Buldon,
Maguindanao.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said the much-awaited result of the investigations on
the controversial March 16 bombing incident which killed 10
students and one teacher in a Buldon school, might also be tackled
in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Cease-fire Monitoring Committee, an independent
group tasked by the government and MILF to investigate the Buldon
tragedy, is expected to come up with their findings this week.
</P>
<P>
The government and MILF technical committee talks had
originally been scheduled for April 9.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF boycotted the talks, saying it would not resume
the talks unless the cease-fire monitoring committee determined
which side was responsible for the March 16 bomb attack.  
</P>
</TEXT>
