<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Surrender in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 33 Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) fighters surrendered to the Philippine
government forces last week, the Presidential Press Office said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the office said a group of 15 MILF members
gave themselves up to the 11th Infantry Battalion in Sultan town
in the southern province of Maguindanao on April 7.
</P>
<P>
Another group of 18 MILF guerrillas surrendered two days later
to the 1st Infantry Division in Lamitan town in Basilan Province,
the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Gen. Edgardo Batenga, presidential consultant on military
affairs, was quoted as saying the surrender of the two MILF groups
within one week was a "big loss to the southern Philippines armed
force in terms of manpower and logistical resources."
</P>
<P>
"These surrenders indicate a breakdown in command and control
of the MILF with its subordinate forces," Batenga said.
</P>
<P>
The press release was issued one day after MILF leaders told
the press that some 5,000 disgruntled Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF) have joined the MILF during the past months.
</P>
<P>
The MILF leaders said these MNLF men defected after being
disillusioned with the slow implementation of the peace deal
signed last September between the MNLF and the government.
</P>
<P>
But the alleged MNLF men's massive defection was quickly denied
by the Philippine military, which accused the MILF leadership of
trying to launch a "propaganda" campaign to defame the government
and the rival MNLF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the MNLF, is currently the
largest anti-government force in the country, with an estimated
membership of 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to accept the peace deal concluded between the
government and MNLF and sought its own peace talks with the
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
