<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Russian Strategic Partnership Important: Rodionov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Russian partnership of
strategic cooperation will not only benefit peace and stability in
the Asia-Pacific region and the world, but also facilitate the
establishment of new, fair, and multipolarized international
political and economic orders, Russian Minister of National
Defense Igor Nikolayevich Rodionov said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a lecture at the Academy of Military Science of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army (PLA), Rodionov said that the strategic
partnership is built on the foundation of common or similar views
that the two countries share on a number of crucial issues about
global development. The partnership has won support from the two
peoples, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the lecture titled "Sino-Russian Partnership Is the Most
Important Factor of Peace and Stability in the Asia-Pacific
Region," he said that both countries oppose some other countries
seeking hegemony and discriminating among countries as leaders and
followers. He said that both countries adhere to the principle of
equality among all members of the international community and work
for the establishment of a new and fair international security
system.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia highly values China's concern about the
eastward expansion of NATO. He said that Russia is diametrically
opposed to the West using the issues of human rights, Tibet, and
Taiwan to apply pressure on China.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the two countries are able to and should
set up and strengthen effective multilateral and bilateral
cooperative frameworks on peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov said that the coordinated stands of the two countries
on global issues have had significant influence on the resolution
of these issues, including disarmament, limitation on offensive
strategic weapons, maintaining the principle of nuclear
non-proliferation, and reform of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Russia will always stick to the "one China"
policy on the Taiwan issue. On the Tibet issue, Russia also holds
that Tibet is part of China, inseparable from the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Rodionov hopes that the two countries will further develop the
partnership of strategic cooperation and conduct intensive and
constructive dialogues in the military and political arena to
improve mutual trust and respect.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
