<HEADLINE> Malaysian Investors Invited to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian investors are
being invited to participate actively in Egypt's economic
development in line with the Middle Eastern country's open door
policy towards foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The offer was made by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal Ahmed El
Ganzoury today at a news conference at the end of his two-day
official visit here.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian investors could take part in at least four big
joint venture projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome Malaysian investors to participate in the
agro-based industry complex in the New Valley Canal where 60,000
acres had been set aside for cotton growing," El Ganzoury said.
</P>
<P>
The second project where Malaysians could be involved is the
upgrading of a shipyard in Alexandria, which is also important to
Egypt, he said.
</P>
<P>
The third project deals with high technology and Malaysian
investors are also encouraged to set up jointly a palm oil
refinery in Egypt to enable the country to cut down on imports of
edible oil amounting to 500 million U.S. dollars a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister hoped that several other projects which
would be jointly set up by the private sector either in Malaysia
or Egypt will bring about a new era of joint ventures between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
El Ganzoury assured Malaysian investors that they would be
given top priority.
</P>
<P>
He said his government had amended 53 laws to ensure that
foreign investments were easy, secure and profitable.
</P>
<P>
"We are also opening our doors to products from other
countries, I promise that Malaysian products will be there in
Egypt," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he had very constructive discussions with his Malaysian
counterpart Mahathir Mohamad and the two signed a Memorandum of
Understanding (MoU) on economic cooperation between the two
countries today.
</P>
<P>
He said businessmen of the two countries also had "very
fruitful" negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, Malaysia and Egypt signed five agreements and MoUs
covering different areas.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Prime Minister said that follow-up action would be
taken to ensure everything starts in the near future as planned.
</P>
<P>
He said he and Mahathir also discussed political issues.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Prime Minister left here for Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
