<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Down on Rate Cut Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
lower today after losing more than half a U.S. cent in the
previous 24 hours, on the back of selling by offshore accounts.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 77.63 U.S. cents, down from
78.17 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Traders cited recent signs that an upswing in economic activity
was so far subdued, encouraging market talks that a rate cut just
could be in the cards.
</P>
<P>
While the United States has taken on a tighter monetary policy
stance in the face of growing inflationary pressures in the
economy, policy in Australia is generally expected to remain
steady to the end of the year on the back of a low inflation
outlook for 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, since the release of much weaker-than-expected local
employment figures last week, a few market participants have been
mulling over the chances of an easing in monetary policy before
year-end.
</P>
<P>
"It is not looking real good for the Australian dollar in the
short term," IBJ foreign exchange manager Shane Spurway said.
</P>
<P>
On cross rates today, the Australian dollar ended at 97.89,
down from 98.82 against the Japanese yen and at 1.3417, down from
1.3431 against the Deutsche mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
