<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Finance Secretary to Bid for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo has confirmed his bid to run for the presidency
in the May 1998 general elections, the Philippine News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo announced his bid during a meeting with a group of
city, municipal and provincial treasurers over the weekend, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
He said his intention to run for the presidency is to sustain
the growing momentum of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"I know the president wants somebody to replace him with
understanding about the economy of the world and the principle of
globalization," de Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he needs the "anointment" of President Fidel Ramos for
his bid, de Ocampo said, "That would certainly help if the
president chooses me. And I have been loyal to the president's
administration that I cannot turn my back on him."
</P>
<P>
Besides de Ocampo, other possible presidential contenders
include Vice President Joseph Estrada, Defense Secretary Renato de
Villa and Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de venecia.
</P>
<P>
But observers here believe the ruling Lakas-NUCD Party will be
divided if de Ocampo and de Venecia, both senior Lakas members,
all want to run next year for the party and compete for the
anointment of Ramos, who is chairman of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, whose single six-year term will expire in May 1998,
cannot run for re-election under the country's current
constitution. Ramos himself has repeatedly confirmed his
determination to step down in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
