<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Shuts down 62,561 Polluting Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China has closed down 62,561
factories causing serious pollution, or 85.5 percent of the
polluting factories that should be shut down, according to the
latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection today show that the closed-down factories included
small paper mills, leather tanning factories, printing and dyeing
mills, coking plants using outdated production processes, and
other factories causing serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
The move was in line with a decree of the State Council last
year that required that all of the country's 15 kinds of
small-sized factories causing serious pollution be close down.
</P>
<P>
These polluters have caused serious environmental problems,
seriously affecting the country's economic development and the
improvement of the living environment.
</P>
<P>
Official figures reveal that the number of polluters that
should be closed had increased to 73,149 by March 31, 1,556 more
than at the end of January.
</P>
<P>
Twenty province-level areas including Beijing, Heilongjiang,
Jiangsu, Guangdong, and Qinghai have nearly completed their
polluter shut-down task, according to the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The shut-down rates of Yunnan Province in southwest China and
Qinghai Province in northwestern China have climbed to 70.9
percent and 97.8 percent respectively from January's 55 percent
and 86 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA To Take Action in World Cup Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- FIFA, soccer's world governing
body, said Tuesday in its headquarters Zurich that it will take
action over brawls, crowd trouble which spoiled recent five World
Cup qualifying games in South America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
FIFA was examining the reports from several national
associations and match officials related to five games earlier
this month: Bolivia-Argentina, Paraguay-Colombia, Sierra
Leone-Ghana, Gabon-Morocco and Nigeria-Guinea.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said its disciplinary committee would meet April 29 to
discuss the two South American games, which saw four players sent
off for fighting or violent conduct.
</P>
<P>
FIFA added that the players expelled were automatically
suspended for at least one match and could face further sanctions.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said its World Cup Committee would discuss what action to
take on the three African games.
</P>
<P>
The Gabon-Morocco game, in Libreville, Gabon on April 6, was
abandoned by the referee in the 55th minute when debris rained
down on the field and fans invaded the pitch.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos on April 5, five soccer fans were reportedly crushed
to death trying to leave the stadium after Nigeria's 2-1 win over
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
And Ghana has protested to FIFA over its 1-1 tie with Sierra
Leone in Freetown on April 5. Sierra Leone scored the equalizer on
a penalty in the 85th minute after a Ghanaian defender was called
for handball. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
