<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Postpones Exchange of Important Visits with Denmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China will postpone its planned
exchange of important visits with Denmark and freeze exchanges and
cooperation with it in the human rights area, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang announced at a routine press
conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In response to a reporter's question, Shen said China
consistently attaches great importance and makes continuous
efforts to developing Sino-Danish relations.
</P>
<P>
He continued that Denmark, however, shows no consideration for
bilateral friendly relations and norms concerning international
relations, intensifying its vain attempts and taking the lead in
putting forth an anti-China motion to This year's annual meeting
of the UN Human Rights Commission in Geneva and sparing no effort
to draw other countries over to its side to confront with China.
</P>
<P>
The activity by Denmark is an interference in China's internal
affairs, he said, adding that it hurts the feeling of the Chinese
people, damages the good atmosphere of the Sino-Danish relations
and sets up an obstacle to the smooth development of bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
As a result to what Denmark has done, he stated, China has to
take necessary response, including delay of planned exchange of
important visits and suspension of contacts cooperation with it in
human rights area.
</P>
<P>
Shen noted that the Sino-Danish relations have been harmed
since the Danish side clings obstinately to its course. "What has
taken place is something that the Chinese side does not like to
see. We sincerely hope that on human rights issue, Denmark will
remove confrontation with China and return to the way to equal
dialogue and cooperation, which is in the fundamental and
long-term interests of the two countries and two peoples." Shen
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
