<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Chinese Region Turns Fruit Into Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- It's not uncommon to eat fruit in
winter in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, as
fruit growing has become a pillar industry there.
</P>
<P>
The region, long famous for its Hami melons and Turpan grapes,
produced 2.2 million tons of fruit from 183,000 ha of farmland
last year, and had 130 kg of fruit per capita, ranking first among
regions and provinces in China.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers grew fruit mainly for self-consumption 20 years
ago, but now the market economy has promoted the cottage industry
into a major source of farmers' income and local revenue.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 households are engaged in fruit growing, while
more than three million farmers make good money from growing fruit
as a sideline.
</P>
<P>
The region, rich in light and heat resources for fruit
cultivation, has built seven national-level fruit production bases
and 20 regional bases, covering 80,000 ha of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The name-brand products, like Hami Melon, Turpan Grape, and
Korla Fragrant Pear, have accounted for 63 percent of the total
output, and sell well at home and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
