<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of HK Drug Abusers Remain Stable for '96: Anti-drug Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Number of Hong Kong's drug
abusers has remained relatively stable, chairman of the Action
Committee Against Narcotics (ACAN) said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chai-nie said that a total of 19,626 abusers of all ages
were reported to Hong Kong's Central Registry of Drug Abuse, which
represented a 1.5 percent increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
But it represented a 3.4 percent decrease from the 1994 figure,
Chan said.
</P>
<P>
So the proportion of local people involved in drug abuse also
remained relatively small, which is about 3.5 per thousand
population, Chan continued.
</P>
<P>
The most commonly abused drugs were heroin (86.6 percent),
cannabis (8.4 percent), cough medicine (3.0 percent), triazolam
(2.9 percent) and methyl amphetamine or "ice" (2.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
The number of drug abusers reported to have abused psycho
tropic substances increased by 28.3 percent in 1996 over the
previous year, from 2,618 to 3,358.
</P>
<P>
The upward trend of female drug abusing persisted in 1996, with
2,417 being reported, which represented a 4.18 percent increase
over the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The ACAN's Research Sub-committee will commission a two-year
study to identify relevant factors affecting the changes in drug
abuse pattern.
</P>
<P>
And the ACAN Sub-committee on Treatment and Rehabilitation will
concurrently examine how to further strengthen the existing
services for female drug abusers and psycho tropic substance
abusers to better cater for their rehabilitation strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
