<HEADLINE> China, Indonesia Hope to Expand Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto and
Vice Chairperson of China's State Science and Technology
Commission Deng Nan expressed the hope here today that the two
countries will expand cooperation in economic and technical
fields.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting at the Merdeka Palace, Soeharto told Deng, who
arrived in Indonesia on April 11 for a 10-day official visit, that
the two countries "have no reason not to strengthen their
cooperation, as we are all developing countries."
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia and China, which established their relations
on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence, have
much common ground, including the fact that they are both rich in
human and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
But, he noted, it is not enough only with rich human and
natural resources. "We should use them better by developing
technology and paying great attention to education."
</P>
<P>
The president proposed that the two countries should start
their technical cooperation from concrete projects, such as in the
fields of industry, agriculture and culture.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who agreed with the president's proposal, said the
technical cooperation will also push forward political, economic
and trade relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
She said that with their large population and broad markets,
the two countries' relations have bright prospects.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Deng and her party also met with State Minister
for Research and Technology Bacharudin Jusuf Habibie.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Habibie said Indonesia will stick to its "one
China" policy. Indonesia will not develop political relations with
Taiwan except in the fields of economy and trade, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
