<HEADLINE> Turkish Senior Army Official to Visit Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- General Cevik Bir, deputy chief of
 General Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces, is to pay a visit to
Israel in May for expansion of military cooperation between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Israel Bir will discuss with Israeli
officials in the military training agreement signed last year to
determine 1997 plans and details about the planned military
exercises, the Daily News quoting sources in the General staff
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The senior army official accompanied by a group of
high-ranking officers, is also expected to inspect the Israel
Aircraft Industries which is responsible for upgrading Turkish Air
Force' F-4 fighters in line with the Israeli-Turkish accord.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Bir will be briefed on Israel's recent
proposal to modernize Turkish M-60 tanks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he will discuss with the Israelis their offer to
refit 48 F-5 fighter jets as well as plans to manufacture a
modern type of rifles to replace the G-3 type small arms
currently used by the Turkish infantry.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli officials are also likely to recommend their
early-warning aircraft to Turkey which has long desired to
possess its own early-warning system.
</P>
<P>
With its Phalcon model, Israel is among the candidates hoping
to get involved in Turkey's bid to buy early-warning aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish armed forces has been playing a key role in
developing defense relations with Israel, and has strongly
defended the necessity of such Turkish-Israeli agreements,
despite pro-Islamic Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan's
reluctance to do so.
</P>
<P>
The ties between Turkey and Israel were greatly enhanced last
year following the signing of a military training agreement and
another accord on defense industry cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreements with Israel have sparked
criticisms from some Middle East countries which believe that
Turkey is aligning itself with the Jewish state to oppose the
interests of the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
