<HEADLINE> Record-high Stamp Revenue Averts Rate Increase in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Post Office will
not increase postage rates this fiscal year thanks to the record
1.1 billion HK dollar (141 million US dollars) profit generated
from special-issue stamps, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Post Office will put the windfall to good use, and is
considering setting up a development fund to improve the services,
Postmaster-General Robert Footman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Post Office will improve the local postage rate
structure in 1997-1998, which means the introduction of economy
services for bulk posting.
</P>
<P>
There will also be an enhanced discount system for the Post
Office's bigger customers, Footman said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that in the next five years the Post Office will
spend 1.2 billion HK dollars (154 million US dollars) improving
services and development.
</P>
<P>
An additional 500 million HK dollars (64 million US dollars)
will be spent on automated and customer services, while the new
mail center being built at Chek Lap Kok will cost another 500
million HK dollars (64 million US dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
