<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Leads to Rising Number of Smoggy Days in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- It has become rarer for a
foreign visitor to Hong Kong to have a panoramic view of Victoria
Harbor as a result of a rocketing number of smoggy days over the
past years, according to local media reports today.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists blame increased pollution and are calling for
a limit on vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A study by the Royal Observatory counted the number of hours
each day for the past three decades when visibility fell to less
than eight kilometers in the Victoria Harbor and outlying areas.
</P>
<P>
Poor visibility caused by weather such as fog, rain, mist and
high humidity was excluded.
</P>
<P>
Results showed that the harbor was blanketed in smog for 450
hours per year in the early 1990s, up from about 180 hours per
year in the 1970s, while outside the harbor, a similar worsening
trend was also recorded.
</P>
<P>
A local environment-friendly organization warned that the smog,
generated by vehicles and construction, would raise hazards for
shipping and air traffic, and urged the government to limit the
vehicle growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
