<HEADLINE> Rockwell Hopes to Join AE 100 Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The head of Rockwell
International, a leading industrial automation and electronics
company in the world, says he hopes his company will be the
supplier of avionic products for the 100-seat jets to be developed
by China, Europe and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Donald R. Beall, chairman and chief executive officer of the
US-based company who is attending a corporate meeting in Beijing,
said today the AE 100 program will be a prospective new field
in which Rockwell can further its cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
He added Rockwell is working with the Aviation Industries of
China (AVIC) to develop avionics for the new 100-seaters, and
"while the decision process continues, we will work aggressively
to maximize our participation" in the program.
</P>
<P>
The AE 100 program, with an estimated cost of two billion US
dollars, is the largest Sino-foreign cooperative project for
China's aircraft manufacturing industry. China aims at the
development of the new jets to help raise industry standards and
meet the demand for regional jetliners in the world over the next
two decades.
</P>
<P>
Rockwell also hopes to sell its GPS-based air traffic
management system to China, Beall said, adding that its new GPS
(global positioning system) manufacturing plants in Shanghai might
be involved in building the air traffic management systems in the
future.
</P>
<P>
He noted the company's interest in co-producing with Chinese
partners Rockwell's air traffic alert and collision avoidance
systems for aircraft. "The software expertise found in China could
help us greatly in these product areas, and we could build on our
long-held relationship with our Chinese airline customers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Collins, a Rockwell subsidiary, has been providing avionics
equipment for Chinese carriers over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
Beall estimated that Rockwell's turnover will hit eight billion
US dollars this year, of which about 15 percent will come from the
Asia-Pacific region. The company's sales in the region are
projected to hit about two billion US dollars by 2001, double
the current figure, and the sales of its electronic products in
China will stand at 200 million US dollars by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Rockwell has invested about 50 million US dollars in China, and
set up four joint ventures, primarily in the automotive industry,
according to Beall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
