<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Series Features Political Struggles in Ancient China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A 60-part TV series depicting the
political struggles involved in China's transformation from a
slave-owning society to feudalism 2,000 years ago recently won
praise from viewers.
</P>
<P>
The China Central Television Station (CCTV), which produced the
show, said that the cost of each segment of the drama "Later Years
of the Zhou Dynasty" was 400,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The station started the showing of the TV series earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
During the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 BC) and the
Warring States (475-221 BC), Chinese society experienced many
tremendous changes.
</P>
<P>
Chinese culture was revitalized in two separate periods, and a
number of thinkers and strategists emerged, such as Lao Zi, the
founder of Taoism, Confucius, a great educator and thinker, and
Sun Wu, who wrote China's earliest-known military work "Master
Sun's Art of War."
</P>
<P>
The series, adapted from some early works on Chinese history,
including "Annals of the Spring and Autumn Period," "Kuo Yu" and
"Tso Chuan," emphasizes historical facts rather than fictional
stories.
</P>
<P>
Director Shen Haofang, who also directed another popular
historical series "Romance of the Three Kingdoms," said that the
filming of such a program is meant to popularize knowledge of
Chinese history and inspire patriotism in young people.
</P>
<P>
Many viewers have noticed that many daily-used words and idioms
originated from stories during the two periods. "It is valid to
popularize ancient Chinese culture through TV programs," said Yang
Shengnan with the Chinese Academy of Social Science, who acted as
a consultant for the drama,
</P>
<P>
The series was co-written by Wang Peigong, Guo Qihong and
Ouyang Yibing, who say they believe that ancient people's
pioneering spirit of reform and their emphasis on talent will
benefit today's social progress.
</P>
<P>
Central China's Henan Province also built a city with Spring
and Autumn Period-style buildings, which has become a favorite
tourist destination, according to the production group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
