<HEADLINE> Motor Vehicle Insurance Booms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics from the
Pacific Ocean Insurance Co., Ltd. show China's total premium
earnings from motor vehicle insurance reached 26 billion yuan last
year, up 25 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounted for nearly 60 percent of the country's
total premium earnings from property insurance, Xu Jinghui, deputy
manager of the Domestic Business Department of the Pacific Ocean
Insurance Co., Ltd, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Motor motor insurance has become the most important source of
income and profit for Chinese property insurance companies, and
will see rapid growth in the coming years, Xu said in an address
to an ongoing seminar on the insurance business, co-sponsored by
the Insurance Institute of China and the Hong Kong Federation of
Insurers (HKFI).
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, China will have 16 million motor vehicles for
civilian use and a 1.2 million kilometers of roads.
</P>
<P>
Based on this, China's premium of motor vehicle insurance is
expected to top 45 billion yuan by the end of this century,
growing at an average annual rate of about 20 percent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese property insures have been competing with one
another for a big slice of the motor vehicle insurance pie, and
are also cooperating with each other in introducing a sound
service system for their clients, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the People's Insurance Company of China (PICC)
still holds 80.7 percent of the country's motor vehicle insurance
market, leaving the rest for other insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
But domestic property insurance companies are also dealing with
a skyrocketing number of compensation claims from their policy
holders.
</P>
<P>
The three giant insurance companies in China, namely, the PICC,
Pacific Ocean Insurance Co. Ltd. and Ping'an Insurance Co. Ltd.
paid a total of 15 billion yuan in claims last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
