<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts on Setup of State Reinsurance Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Experts from the Reinsurance
Company of the People's Insurance Company of China (PICC) have
suggested that China set up a state reinsurance company just as
other developing countries have done, in order to curb the market
disorder and develop a national reinsurance industry.
</P>
<P>
China plans to establish some policy insurance companies
separating from the commercial firms to further its
commercialization of the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
The policy insurance companies to be formed include a company
dealing in agricultural insurance, one that specializes in export
credit insurance and a state reinsurance business.
</P>
<P>
PICC Reinsurance, one of the three subsidiaries of the PICC,
now functions as a state reinsurance company authorized by the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
"But it is unfair for other Chinese insurance companies if PICC
Reinsurance continues its role as a state reinsurance company, as
it is a commercial company," a Chinese insurance official said.
</P>
<P>
Many other Chinese insurers, including Pacific Ocean Insurance
and Ping'an Insurance Co., Ltd., have started businesses in the
country's reinsurance market, which formerly was monopolized by
PICC.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that the state reinsurance company to be set
up will be a combination of a policy and commercial insurance
firm, mainly dealing with compulsory reinsurance business, and
playing the leading role in China's reinsurance market.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed out that a few commercial reinsurance
companies should be built, and a pool should be established among
all insurance companies in Taiwan, Hong Kong and the inland areas
by both home and overseas Chinese to handle special insurance
needs such as coverage for natural disasters or nuclear hazards.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the total income of the reinsurance
industry in China's inland areas will be around 23 billion yuan by
the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0150 </DOCNO>
