<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Blind Chinese to Become Massagists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- New measures taken by certain
Chinese authorities will enable more blind people in the country
to become massagists.
</P>
<P>
The China Massage Center for the Blind plans to train 20,000
blind people in massage techniques and 500 key teaching personnels
by the year 2000, according to a report in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
At present, about 10,000 blind massagists are working at 1,630
establishments and clinics across the country.
</P>
<P>
The center will encourage local massage bodies and training
centers run by blind people to train those pursuing massage
careers while inviting massage departments in the country's three
medical colleges and technical schools to support such training,
Cheng Weiping, deputy office director of the center, told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The center has compiled and published 18 kinds of teaching
materials and teaching plans for such medical massage work, in
both Braille and Chinese, Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China's development plan for disabled people
during the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) has designated that
national and local federations for the disabled be independently
in charge of training and employment of those pursuing massage
careers.
</P>
<P>
The state has basically completed the drafting of regulations
and policies for the appraisal of technical titles for blind
people involved in massage career, as well as for their training,
employment and administration, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Massage has been a major field of work for blind people in
China. Others have found handicraft jobs such as knitting,
packaging of products, tuning of musical instruments and jobs as
telephone operators.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 blind people received training in performing
massage last year, three times the annual training record in the
1991-1995 period, the newspaper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
