<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Woman Police Officer Jailed for Stealing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A woman police officer of
Singapore was sentenced to seven years in prison for stealing 800
Singapore dollars (about 556 U.S. dollars) from a Myanmar
overstayer, local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the court was told Yvonne Yeo Seow Hwee, 22,
was the officer on duty at the Central Police Division lock-up
when the incident happened two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Yeo searched the overstayer, 36-year-old Myo Mahn, who was
being detained, and found a coin box and a pouch containing stacks
of money.
</P>
<P>
Before registering the contents, the officer secretly pocketed
a wad of 50-dollar bills and wrote out a prison's property receipt
which accounted only for the rest of the contents.
</P>
<P>
The detainee disputed the amount in the receipt and Yeo
panicked, the report said. It said she then hid the cash in a can
of air freshener in the toilet, and the theft was later
discovered.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said she stole because of family circumstances. But the
district judge said he felt the need to impose a deterrent
sentence, because Yeo was tasked with upholding justice, but she
had abused that power, the judge said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
