<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Insurance Seeing Rapid Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- China's total premium income
generated from life insurance services hit 33 billion yuan last
year, an increase of 70 percent over 1995 figures, statistics from
the Ping'an Insurance Co., Ltd. show.
</P>
<P>
He Zhiguang, deputy manager of the Ping'an Insurance Company
Shanghai branch, said that about half of the nearly 300 million
Chinese urban residents, whose annual incomes are showing stable
growth, have considered buying life insurance.
</P>
<P>
The per capita annual income of urban residents was about 4,500
yuan last year, which made life insurance costs more affordable at
a time when China is reshaping its social welfare system.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank predicts that by the turn of the century, the
total income of China's insurance industry will reach 250 billion
yuan, half of which comes from life insurance premium income.
</P>
<P>
"This creates a big life insurance market for both home and
overseas insurers, and one which has kept growing at a
double-digit rate over the past few years," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the country adopted a law on insurance administration
last year, a well-regulated and standardized life insurance market
has taken shape in China, he noted.
</P>
<P>
But compared with other countries in the world, China's life
insurance market still remains underdeveloped, he added.
</P>
<P>
Data show that the per capita spending on life insurance
services of Chinese residents was no more than 1.4 US dollars last
year, with the total premium income of life insurance accounting
for less than 0.3 percent of the country's gross national product.
</P>
<P>
China now has five nationwide players on the life insurance
market, including the three giant insurers -- the People's
Insurance Company of China, Pacific Ocean Insurance Co., ltd,
Ping'an Insurance Co., Ltd. -- and New China and Taikang companies
set up last year.
</P>
<P>
The American Insurance International Group(AIG) has also
started business in Shanghai and Guangzhou, as well as a joint
venture insurance company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
