<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Cuts Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- In a major attempt to give a
boost to the cash-starved Indian industry, the Reserve Bank of
India (RBI) today cut interest rates by 1 percent to 11 percent,
abolished cash reserve ratio on interbank liabilities and reduced
interest rates on short-term domestic deposits.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the slack season credit policy, RBI Governor C.
Rangarajan told a press conference in Mumbai (Bombay) that the cut
in interest rates would send an "effective signal" to the
cash-starved Indian industry and give freedom to banks to evolve
their own methods of assessing working capital needs of industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the credit policy for 1997-98 (April-March), the interest
rate on domestic term deposits for maturity of 30 days and up to
one year was reduced to 9 percent from the present 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has also adopted some financial schemes to
attract foreign exchange from non-resident Indians, according to
the Press Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
It also attempted to improve the credit delivery system and
give complete freedom to banks on credit dispensation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
