<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Pledges Safety of German Embassy, Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran pledged here today it will
protect foreign nationals in the country and would not allow
extremist Muslim students to capture German embassy as what
happened to the U.S. Embassy here 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri said at a press
conference "We have observed and will keep observing the
international rules and regulations."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian speaker made the statement while answering a
question posed by Xinhua on his stance to toward the students'
warning to seize the German Embassy unless the German government
makes an apology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
On Monday afternoon, about 400 students clashed with some
1,000 anti-riot policemen in front of the German Embassy and
dozens of extremist students were arrested as they tried to break
through the protection line a bid to remove the German flag at
the top of the embassy building.
</P>
<P>
The incident induced grave concern over the safety and
security of foreign embassies and foreign nationals working and
living in Iran.
</P>
<P>
At present some 500 Germans are living and working in Iran, but
about 30 engineers from the Siemens have left the country since
the anti-German wave started in the Islamic republic Thursday
after the Berlin court announced its verdict accusing top
political leadership in Iran of ordering the assassination of four
Kurdish opposition leaders in a Berlin Mykonos restaurant in
1992, .
</P>
<P>
"Our people would have never done that and will never do
that," he replied to the question on whether what happened to the
U.S. embassy here 18 years ago would recur.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian extremist students occupied the U.S. Embassy to
Tehran and held all the embassy staff hostage in 1979 when the
Islamic Revolution began, and the seizure lasted 444 days.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old speaker made a guarantee that the foreign
embassies and their nationals will be safe and in no danger
despite the escalating tension between Iran and Germany
following the Berlin court verdict.
</P>
<P>
He said "we have an obligation to protect the lives of foreign
nationals in Iran just as we have an obligation to protect the
lives of our own people," adding that "Our people are not the kind
who would endanger the lives of foreigners living in this
country."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Iran was making the pledge despite that fact
that "the Germans have not been able, or being incompetent, to
keep counter-revolutionaries off our embassy in Bonn."
</P>
<P>
They raided the Iranian embassy many times, set fire to parts
of the embassy compound and harassed the Iranian employees, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the verdict by the Berlin court accusing top political
leadership in Iran of ordering the assassination of four Kurdish
opposition leaders in a Berlin Mykonos restaurant in 1992, he said,
"it is regretful for the Germans to have undertaken such an
illogical measure and have brought into existence such crisis."
</P>
<P>
Iran has launched a nationwide anti-German demonstration with
tens of thousands of people turning out in 12 cities to protest
against the Berlin court ruling over the Mykonos case.
</P>
<P>
The protesters urged the government to sever its diplomatic
and economic ties with Germany and prosecute 24 German companies
which exported chemical weapons to Iraq during the eight-year
war with Iran starting from 1980.
</P>
<P>
On the question whether Iran will downgrade or cut relations
with Germany, he replied that the government would examine the
case and respond to the Parliament's request accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri, who is a front-runner in the 7th presidential
election scheduled in May 23, stressed "We must keep
concentrating on our own national interests before anything
else."
</P>
<P>
On the relations between Iran and European Union (EU)
countries, he said, "what the European Union countries are doing
is even more illogical than what Germans have done."
</P>
<P>
"These EU countries are rushing into something whose dimensions
are not as yet understood by them," he noted.
</P>
<P>
All the 15-EU-member countries, except Greece, have recalled
their ambassadors in a protest against the involvement of Iranian
leaders in the assassination of Kurdish opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We are not worried whether the EU countries sever ties or
recall their ambassadors," he said.
</P>
<P>
The speaker noted that the EU decision against Iran is no
bigger than the U.S. D' Amato bill of imposing sanctions against
oil companies to invest over 40 million U.S. dollars in Iran and
Libya, which failed to harm Iran or bring the Iranians to their
knees.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court verdict sparked a fierce diplomatic battle
between Iran and Germany. The two sides had recalled their
ambassadors and expelled four diplomats from each side.
</P>
<P>
Besides EU countries, countries like Australia and New Zealand
have also recalled their ambassadors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
