<HEADLINE> Drop of International Crude Oil Prices Raises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices in the world
market have crashed below the Nigeria's official selling price of
17 U.S. Dollars per barrel, causing major concern among economy
watchers in the Africa's largest oil-producing country.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of petroleum Export Countries (OPEC) said on
Monday that the price of its basket of crudes, including
Nigeria's Bonny Light, dropped to 16.91 U.S. Dollars per barrel
compared with 17.74 U.S. Dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
The new price represents nine cents or 0.5 percent below the
Nigerian government's budget price of 17 U.S. Dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Unrestrained production, particularly by members of OPEC, was
linked to the falling oil prices. Total output by the
organization last month was 27.175 million barrels per day, which
was 2.142 million above the group's ceiling of 25.033 million.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has projected a foreign exchange
revenue of 9.202 billion U.S. Dollars from oil exports this
fiscal year based on the selling price of 17 U.S. Dollars per
barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
