<HEADLINE> Australia to Discuss Iran Issue With Other Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia will hold discussions
with the United States, Canada and members of the European Union
before taking any further action against Iran over its alleged
terrorist activities, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said
today.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Brisbane for a federal cabinet meeting
today, Downer said, "We want to have discussions with our partners
before taking any further action beyond the recall of the
ambassador."
</P>
<P>
Australia recalled its ambassador, Stuart Hume, from Iran after
the announcement of the German High Court last week that Iran had
ordered a group of terrorists into Germany to assassinate Kurdish
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Downer said he had not received full details of the German High
Court decision, but the federal government wanted "very carefully
to assess" what the court had said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has gained much out of the former Labor government's
refusal to back a U.S. trade boycott against Iran in 1995, with
exports to the Islamic republic having since topped 1 billion
Australian dollars (780 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the last financial year alone, exports to Iran reached 540
million Australian dollars (421 million U.S. dollars), including
470 million dollars in wheat, coal, wool and sugar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
