<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Ready for Civilian Rule, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's military administration
has restated its commitment to the program of transition to
democratically-elected civilian government.
</P>
<P>
In a speech on Monday, Head of State General Sani Abacha
called on the armed forces to increasingly pursue their
constitutional roles as the deadline from the military's
disengagement from governance approaches.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that sanctions against Nigeria by western
countries as the United States and members of the European Union,
together with the ailing national economy, had adversely affected
operations of the Nigerian Air Force (NAF).
</P>
<P>
But it was gratifying that creative innovativeness of the force
had cushioned the adverse impact, Abacha told the opening of the
NAF Reunion Week in Kaduna, an important military base of the
armed forces in northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, including embargo on the sales and service of
military wares, have added difficulty to the supply of spare
parts for military equipment since they were imposed following
the Nigerian government's execution of some minority tribe
activists in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the confrontation and hostility by a section of
the international community, we shall remain undeterred in our
goal of enthroning a democratic dispensation," Abacha said.
</P>
<P>
According to the transition program, the military
administration will terminate with the installation of civilian
government on October 1, 1998 after the general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
