<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Enjoys Trade Surplus With U.S. in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, Africa's largest
oil-producting country, enjoyed in 1996 a trade surplus of five
billion U.S. Dollars with the United States, with a total trade
volume of 6.6 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Information Service said in an annual trade review
that Nigeria exported 5.8 billion U.S. Dollars worth of goods,
mainly oil products, to the U.S. in 1996, as against an import of
816 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the surplus on the Nigerian side is 4.2 billion U.S.
Dollars, the review said, adding that Nigeria is now the No. 57
foreign market for the U.S. in terms of size.
</P>
<P>
The review put the U.S. direct investment in Nigeria in 1995
at 5.95 million U.S. Dollars, representing an increase of 84.8
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. investment in Nigeria is concentrated largely in the
manufacturing sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The review listed inadequate and poorly-maintained
infrastructure, confusing and inconsistent regulations as leading
obstacles to increased U.S. investment in the west African
country, despite the government's many efforts to boost direct
foreign investment in the last few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
