<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Launches "Buy Russian" Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today called on Russians to give preference to national goods in
order to help the country's ailing industries.
</P>
<P>
In a radio address, Yeltsin said that his appeal is buttressed
by better quality of goods produced in the country.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the Russian market has been filled
with foreign-made goods.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come to resolve a new task. I want our people to
give preference to Russia-made products, such as wear costumes,
shoes, refrigerators and furniture," said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin stressed that it did not mean there is to be
a tough protectionism to ban foreign goods from the Russian
market, but "Russia-made goods should excel in quality."
</P>
<P>
"Russia should encourage honest competition. Any administrative
pressure is inadmissible," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Some reports say that up to half of the food consumed by
Russians is imported and that Russians prefer in many cases to buy
Western products, particularly electronic goods, because the
equivalent items manufactured in Russia do not meet world
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
