<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Official Forecasts Increase in Arms Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official has
reportedly revealed that Israel expects to export about 1.7
billion U.S. dollars of weapons this year and 2 billion
U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministry director-general Ilan Biran made the remarks
in an interview published on this week's Bitahon, a magazine of
Israeli Defense Ministry employees.
</P>
<P>
However, Biran did not elaborate on his assessment of arms
exports, and in fact the magazine does not even quote him
directly making these assessments.
</P>
<P>
"Regarding security exports, the Defense Ministry
director-general is a man of good news," Bitahon reads.
</P>
<P>
"He speaks of a total of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 and
of a goal for exports to the tune of 2 billion U.S. dollars in
1998-99."
</P>
<P>
Biran's forecast contrasts with that of senior executives in
the defense industries, who say Israel is facing increasing
competition to sell weapons.
</P>
<P>
In mid-March, senior Israeli defense executives warned that
unless the industry embarked on significant layoffs and
eliminated duplication, exports would decline and research and
development would be underfunded.
</P>
<P>
However, other executives said Biran's forecasts are in line
with those of the larger defense contractors in Israel, who view
new markets in Asia and Western Europe as having great growth
potential.
</P>
<P>
Israel's arms exports last year were reported at 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars, largely because of the 650 million-U.S.-dollar deal
which Israel Aircraft Industries signed with Turkey for the
latter's upgrading of 54 F-4 Phantom jets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
