<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Pledges Safety of German Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran pledged here today that
it will not allow extremist Moslem students to capture the
German Embassy here as what happened to the American embassy
18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri said at a press
conference "We have observed and will keep observing the
international rules and regulations."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian speaker made the statement while answering a
question posed by Xinhua on his stance toward students' warning
to seize the German Embassy unless the German government makes an
apology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Monday afternoon, about 400 students clashed with 1,000
anti-riot policemen in front of the German Embassy and dozens of
extremist students were arrested as they tried to break through
the protective line a bid to seize the German flag at the top of
German Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The incident roused grave concern over the safety and security
of foreign embassies and foreign nationals working and living in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Our people would have never done that and will never do
that,' he replied to the question on whether Iran would repeat
what happened to the American embassy 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old speaker made a guarantee that the foreign
embassies and foreign nationals will be safe and in no danger
despite the escalating tension between Iran and Germany following
the Berlin court verdict.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we have an obligation to protect the lives of
foreign nationals in Iran just as we have an obligation to
protect the lives of our own people."
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, "this is on the conditions that the
Germans have not been able, or being incompetent, to keep
counter- revolutionaries off our embassy in Bonn."
</P>
<P>
They raided the Iranian embassy many times, set fire to
parts of the embassy and harassed the Iranian employees, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the verdict by the Berlin court charging top political
leadership in Iran of the ordering the assassination of four
Kurdish opposition leaders in a Berlin restaurant in 1992, he
said, "it is regretful for the Germans to have undertaken such an
illogical measure and have brought into existence such crisis."
</P>
<P>
Iran has launched a nationwide anti-German wave with tens
of thousands of people turning out in 12 cities to protest
the insult by the Berlin court in the Mykonos case. The
demonstrators urged the government to sever the diplomatic and
economic ties with Germany and prosecute 24 German companies
which exported chemical weapons to Iraq during the eight-year
war with Iran from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
On a question whether Iran will downgrade or cut relations
with Germany, he replied, "the government would examine the
case and respond to the Parliament request accordingly."
</P>
<P>
Nateq-Nouri, who is a front-runner in the 7th presidential
election scheduled in May 23, stressed "We must keep
concentrating on our own national interests before anything else."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
