<HEADLINE> Dutch Flower Company Eyes China As New Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands Euro-Asia Flower
Group plans to transfer part of its production base to China, the
group's president Bin Yang announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Yang said the group, which is a combination of 14 flower
companies in the Netherlands, France and Belgium, has already set
up in Ghina factories to manufacture cold storage facilities as
well as greenhouses and farms to young plants and bulbs of tulips,
roses, Gladioli, chrysanthemum, hyacinths and connassions.
</P>
<P>
Yang also said that the company will also set up factories to
produce flower soil, flower medicine, flower packaging and dry
flowers in China.
</P>
<P>
Yang, a Dutch Chinese, made the remarks at his company's
ongoing month-long tulip show in Beijing, which ends on May 12.
The company's tulips are also being shown in Shanghai, Tianjin,
Jinan and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
He said that his company has started construction near Beijing
Airport for Asia's biggest flower supermarket and auction market,
which is scheduled for completion in Beijing at the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the businessman added, China's cheap labor force is
one of the factors that encouraged his company to move part of its
operations to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
