<HEADLINE> Egyptian Envoy Heads for U.S. on Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President's Political
Advisor Osama el-Baz left here for Washington on a stepped-up
diplomatic drive to revive the stalled Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
His visit will be part of a flurry of wide-spread diplomatic
contacts Egypt is launching in the coming weeks to lobby the
United States and the European Union for new initiatives that it
hopes to salvage the faltering peace process.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-departure statement, Baz said in Washington he will
meet with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, U.S. Mideast
Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross as well as with the U.S. National
Security Adviser to discuss means to break the current Mideast
peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
"I will discuss the U.S. initiatives with these officials and
get acquainted with their view regarding the EU idea," said Baz.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Arab attempts to activate the European role, Baz
said that Arabs welcome a European role but such a role should be
coordinated with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
In fact the Europeans are joining hands with the U.S. in order
to hammer out a proposal, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Europeans are discussing their initiative with the U.S. to
stage a joint European-U.S. initiative," he added, saying that he
was carrying Egypt's own proposals but refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has told reporters that Baz will
brief the U.S. side on Egypt's ideas, which fall "within the
framework of its well-known lines."
</P>
<P>
Moussa also outlined the objectives of Egypt's intensive
diplomatic campaign underway, saying that its aim is to reach a
springboard taking into consideration Jerusalem, the settlements,
implementation of Oslo agreements on troop redeployment, and
resumption of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian diplomatic move followed the separate initiatives
proposed by the U.S. and EU to revive Israeli Palestinian talks
had flopped, failing to discourage Israel from a controversial
Jewish housing project in East Jerusalem, a condition the
Palestinians insist for resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak sent his top envoy to meet
U.S. officials to break the peace deadlock just one day after he
had talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's in Cairo,
reportedly at the request of U.S. President Bill Clinton who sent
a message to Mubarak Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians refuse to hold talks with Israel until it
stops work on the 6,500-house settlement on the edge of Arab East
Jerusalem, a project that has stalled the peace talks and sparked
almost daily clashes in the occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
Arafat today will leave here for Valletta, Malta to attend the
Euro-Mediterranean conference and meet with Ross. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
