<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Host Two NATO Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is preparing to host two
military exercises of NATO member countries under the alliance's
schedule, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Troops from the United States, Canada, Italy, Norway, the
Netherlands, Germany, Belgium, Spain and Britain will reportedly
participate in the maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The first one, named Ardent Ground '97, is to be conducted in
Turkey's European territory of Thrace, the closest part of the
country to its traditional rival Greece.
</P>
<P>
Ardent Ground '97, which will be backed by air support, aims
to improve the combat ability of NATO's light mobile land forces,
military sources said.
</P>
<P>
Distant Thunder, a second Turkey-hosted exercise, is expected
to be carried out by land and sea forces in western Anatolia
and the eastern Mediterranean between April 28 and May 18 with
the participation of Italy, Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Greece will take part in neither of the two military
exercises due to its bad relationship with Ankara, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that, however, the troops from Turkey and
Greece would participate in a joint military exercise in the
United States between June 15 and July 4.
</P>
<P>
This joint military exercise, which will also be attended by
American, Bulgarian, and Moldovan troops, is aimed at
strengthening military coordination among the participant
countries for regional stability in the Balkans and in neighboring
countries, a high-ranking officer form the Turkish Armed Forces
said.
</P>
<P>
Greece usually does not take part in joint military
exercises organized in Turkey and generally distances itself from
those maneuvers in which Turkey is involved.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have long been at odds over a number of
issues including the limits of air space, mineral rights below
the Aegean Sea as well as the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
