<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus to Enhance Operation in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The airlines of the
Asia-Pacific region will continue to experience the strongest
growth of any region in the world over the next two decades, an
Airbus Industrie official said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, John Leahy, senior vice president and
head of the Commercial Directorate, said that the Asia-Pacific
Region will become the dominant world market for new civil
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest market forecast for the region from
Airbus released here today, passenger traffic to, from and within
the region will rise at an average rate of 6.4 percent per year
over the forecast period, compared with the world average of 5.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Asia-Pacific region is a core market for
Airbus Industrie, accounting for one quarter of all sales recorded
by the consortium to date, with over 400 widebody aircraft
currently in service with 31 operators.
</P>
<P>
This higher than average growth for the region will generate a
requirement for triple the number of airline seats currently
available, rising from today's level of around 416,000 to 1.3
million, or 32 percent of total world capacity.
</P>
<P>
He said that Airbus Industrie predicts a high requirement for
replacement aircraft and, with some airlines expected to replace
current fleets twice over, this market will be equal to the
current fleet size of 1,800.
</P>
<P>
He said that this leaves a requirement for 2,300 additional
aircraft to meet growth, adding that with an existing backlog of
almost 500 aircraft already ordered by Asia-Pacific airlines,
potential sales in the region therefore total some 3,600 aircraft,
valued at 375 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1970, Airbus Industrie is a multi-national
consortium owned by Europe's four leading aerospace manufacturers
and it has grown to become the world's second largest supplier of
large civil aircraft with a product line covering everything from
short haul single aisle market to the ultra-long rang sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Further Eases Closure on West Bank, Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army today
further eased a total closure imposed on the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, allowing more Palestinians to return to their jobs
inside Israel.
</P>
<P>
As of this morning, Palestinians, married and aged over 30,
from the West Bank and Gaza Strip will be permitted to
enter Israel for work, according to an announcement issued by
the Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
In addition, visits to Palestinian "security prisoners" will
be renewed, but limited to 300 per day, reads the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel imposed the total closure on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip immediately after a suicide bombing attack
in a down town coffee shop in Tel Aviv, which left three
women dead and over 50 injured.
</P>
<P>
The closure has barred tens of thousands of Palestinians
from returning to their jobs inside Israel, and from traveling
between the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and
army chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak decided to ease the
closure, allowing 20,000 Palestinian workers enter into Israel,
</P>
<P>
The permits then was only to be given to married men
over the age of 45.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the Israeli army allowed Gaza Strip
residents in the West Bank to return to the strip, as well
as West Bank residents in the Gaza Strip to travel home.
</P>
<P>
The army was also letting Palestinians who are married to
Jerusalem residents with Israeli identity cards to enter the
city.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, another 22 Palestinian ambulances were allowed to
enter Israel on an emergency basis, bringing to 36 the
number of ambulances allowed to cross into Israel from the
Palestinian autonomous areas.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army said that one hundred Palestinian laborers
who have jobs in tourist industries were also being let in
Israel, but stressed that all entrance permits are subjected
to strict security clearances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
