<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villages Undergoing Uurbanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Booming township and village
enterprises in east China's Shandong Province have turned
grass-roots units into corporations through mergers.
</P>
<P>
Dingjia Village in the city of Laizhou set up the Shandong
Hongxiang Electrical Appliances Group Corporation, which has
gradually become popular, while the its original is no longer in
use.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 villages changes their names owing to annexation
and mergers in the province's east coastal areas over the past few
years. Local residents began to use new names or addresses in
writing letters.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, annexation and mergers are used
as means to overcome unbalanced development of villages.
</P>
<P>
Qiansongjia Village in Shandong's Longkou city, has grown into
the Nanshan Group Corporation from a once poverty-stricken area.
The village established factories of textiles, alumina, and wood,
and badly needed to obtain more land resources and manpower as its
production scale rapidly expanded.
</P>
<P>
The idea of annexation met with immediate support from the
neighboring poor villages and authorities concerned, and three of
the villages have been merged into the group beginning in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The village, once only one sq km in area, now covers 10 sq km,
and its population has more than tripled to 3,700. The
village-turned-group, with 1.2 billion yuan of fixed assets and
20,000 staff and workers, produced annual sales worth of 1.6
billion yuan last year, and was graded a national-level
first-class township enterprise by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The group built villa-like buildings for newly-merged villagers
and employed them in factories. "We didn't expect such great
changes before annexation. We lost our village's names, but we
make more money, and live a more cultured life," one farmer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
