<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Records Largest Quarterly Price Fall Since 1961 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Prices dropped by 0.3 percent
in the first quarter this year, the biggest quarterly fall since
1961.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by Statistics New Zealand today showed that
the 0.3 percent fall was attributed to lower mortgage and other
retail lending rates, and falling prices for transport, clothes
and footwear.
</P>
<P>
The previous biggest fall in a quarter came in March 1961, when
prices dipped by 0.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the yearly basis, Statistics NZ said prices for the year
ending March rose 1.8 percent, lower than most economists
predicted.
</P>
<P>
The main factor pushing prices down was a sharp fall in retail
lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Floating rates for mortgages have now slid to around 9.5
percent, much lower than a year ago, and some economists forecast
they are likely to go down further on the back of today's
inflation news.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
