<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 08:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Million Pilgrims Head toward Mena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 15 (Xinhua) -- About two million pilgrims
converged on the holy site of Mena in Saudi Arabia to start the
first Hajj rituals today.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims, 1.2 million from the Arab and Islamic world and
the rest, the Saudis and residents in the Kingdom, would perform
short prayers either at Kheif mosque or stay there in Mena to
spend the whole day, according to Kuwait News Agency (KUNA)
reports from Mecca.
</P>
<P>
After sunrise Wednesday, the pilgrims will ascend to Mount
Arafat for Hajj.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia announced earlier April 16 would be the climax of
Hajj when the pilgrims would march to Mount Arafat. The following
day would be the beginning of Eid Al-Adha, when pilgrims
symbolically stone the devil and slaughter sheep and other
animals.
</P>
<P>
Pilgrims have been arriving in the kingdom for weeks and Saudi
television shows footage every day of pilgrims walking around the
Holy Kaaba in Mecca Grand Mosque.
</P>
<P>
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, Custodian of the two holy
mosques, called upon all governmental departments earlier this
month to offer maximum services to help pilgrims perform their
rituals with utmost ease and comfort and in an atmosphere of peace
and security.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Hajj authorities have intensified their efforts to
ease traffic for pilgrims and secure their needs.
</P>
<P>
Local security and traffic officers and staff took positions
at main centers to ease difficulties facing the two million
pilgrims rushing to the limited area of Mena which they have
to reach before noon, KUNA said.
</P>
<P>
Helicopters and highly sophisticated communication systems were
used to monitor the movement of pilgrims and ease any
bottlenecks hampering the process.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of health centers have been established in various
areas to provide services.
</P>
<P>
High-tech fire extinguishing devices were also employed to
automatically, quickly and forcefully sprinkle water to cap any
fire possible during the Hajj festival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
