<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Province Builds Modern Highway Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan province
is pooling efforts to build a modern highway network to upgrade
its outdated transport facilities before the next century.
</P>
<P>
The provincial authorities plan to invest a total of 21 billion
yuan in building highways exclusively for motor vehicles in the
1996-2000 period, more than three times that of the 1991-1995
period.
</P>
<P>
With the investment, Yunnan will have a highway network by 2000
that provides access to the sea on the east via neighboring
Guangxi, connects it with Myanmar on the west, and with Laos and
Thailand on the south, and with neighboring Sichuan and Guizhou
provinces on the north.
</P>
<P>
Underdeveloped transport facilities have been the main factor
impeding Yunnan's economic expansion. With 94 percent of its
394,000-sq-km-territory mountains and hills, and a location far
from the coast and economically developed areas, Yunnan has been
one of the poorest areas in China.
</P>
<P>
The province built its first Grade 2 highway exclusively for
motor vehicles at the end of 1980s. The 120-km road on the
outskirts of Kunming, the provincial capital, increased the speed
for motor vehicles from 40 km per hour to 80 km, after
enlightening local people on the importance of good roads.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has since built 1,969 km of highways above Grade 2, and
a high-grade highway network has been formed in an area with
Kunming as the center of a radius of 200 km. The high-grade roads,
however, only account for 2.8 percent of Yunnan's total length of
roads.
</P>
<P>
The province is now building more than 400 km of Grade 1
highways, which will increase the speed of motor vehicles to above
120 km per hour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Plant Trees To Earn Pension For Their Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- During the past month young
people in the town of Chaoyang in east China's Anhui province have
been busy planting fruit trees as a means to earn old-age pension
for their parents, according to China Forest News.
</P>
<P>
This year more than 600 hectare of fruit trees have been
planted in Chaoyang located in Lingbi county.
</P>
<P>
"Starting from several years ago, this old-age pension tree
planting effort has brought more pocket money for the old in the
town," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In rural China most old people do not get certain monthly
pensions as do those living in urban areas. The lack of pocket
money often caused family disputes between the aged parents and
their children.
</P>
<P>
Trees, especially fruit trees planting, is usually an important
source of cash for rural Chinese. In China, forest has long been
viewed as a "green bank". 
</P>
</TEXT>
