<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smooth Beijing-Kowloon Railway Traffic Guaranteed Against Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 15 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
will give top priority in this year's flood prevention to ensure
smooth operation of the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, which runs more
than 720 km throughout.
</P>
<P>
There are several hundred reservoirs along the railway within
the province's boundary, 199 of which pose a threat during flood
seasons to the line.
</P>
<P>
Most of the reservoirs were built in the 1950s and 1960s, with
no consideration for railway's safety taken into account, and now
operate in poor conditions, vulnerable to flood.
</P>
<P>
Primary Party and government officials above township level are
held accountable for designated reservoirs in flood control and
the safety of the railway, which links China's capital with Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
An inspection for hidden perils is going strong at all the
reservoir areas. Some reservoirs are required to operate with
limited storage of water, and some even empty their stored water,
to prepare for potential flood pressure.
</P>
<P>
Localities have increased their contacts with railway
departments to coordinate efforts in flood prevention, while
hydrological and meteorological departments inform railway
stations of potential risks.
</P>
<P>
Materials for flood prevention are being carried to where
necessary, as an anti-flood campaign goes full speed along the
line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
