<HEADLINE> Singapore Firm Makes Largest Foreign Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore government-linked
Neptune Orient Lines (NOL) will spend 825 million U.S. dollars to
buy the U.S. shipping group APL Ltd. in the largest foreign
acquisition by a Singapore firm, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Straits Times, the deal will create one of the
world's biggest fleets, with 113 vessels, including 76 container
ships.
</P>
<P>
The deal, expected to be completed late this year, is subject
to regulatory approval in the United States as well as the nod
from APL shareholders. In Singapore, the Stock Exchange of
Singapore (SES) has granted a waiver to NOL from obtaining its
shareholders' approval for the deal, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that NOL's group turnover is likely to increase
to 6 billion Singapore dollars (about 4.17 billion U.S. dollars)
following the takeover, making it the second largest local company
on the SES after the Singapore Telecom.
</P>
<P>
APL is listed on the New York and Pacific Stock Exchanges and
is a leading global transportation and logistics company providing
container shipping, cargo distribution and other related services.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
