<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OSCE Backs Italian-Led Military Operation in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) today backed an Italian-led
multinational military operation in Albania to protect humanitarian
relief delivery.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, OSCE
Chairman-in-Office Niels Helveg Petersen said that OSCE will play
a "guiding and liaison role" in both civilian and military
aspects of the mission code-named "Operation Alba (Dawn)."
</P>
<P>
The operation, which was announced to start shortly after
midnight on Monday, was designed to put Albania back on the road
to normality and promote national reconciliation in the Balkan
country, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Albania, ravaged by unrest and violence in recent months, needs
assistance from the international community, especially with the
distribution of medicine which must be protected by military
forces, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Petersen, who is the Danish foreign minister, also confirmed
the dispatch of Danish soldiers for the operation.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to give the size of the Danish contingent
because it needs to be approved by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Italy has pledged to contribute the largest contingent of 2,500
troops to the multinational force. Apart from Italy and Denmark,
the other countries which will take part in the operation are
France, Spain, Turkey, Greece, Romania and Austria.
</P>
<P>
The advance parties from Italy and France have already been
deployed in Albania to prepare for the arrival of the main
contingents.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 soldiers from Italy, France and Spain were set
to land at the Albanian port of Durres early on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
In Athens, Greek military sources said that the first units of
the 760-strong Greek contingent are expected to travel to Vlore by
sea on Thursday to be followed by the rest to fly to Tirana on
Saturday and next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The force will build up to its maximum of some 6,000 troops in
three months when all contingents arrive, Italian chief of the
Defense Staff Admiral Guido Venturoni. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
