<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Calls for Cooperation from Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand called on the private sector to work together with
the government for the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function held in honor of the newly formed
cabinet by the local business community here Monday, Chand urged
the private sector to create a smooth environment for the
mobilization of domestic capital.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that his government, which came to power one month
ago, will continue market-oriented policies and facilitate the
private sector with necessary assistance.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the need to identify areas of
comparative advantages and make Nepal's presence in international
market by consolidating the internal market and enhancing
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The government has adopted a flexible policy to create a
secured environment for both local and foreign investors, Chand
said, adding that it is ready to solve any hurdles in business and
industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Padma Jyoti, president of the Federation of Nepalese Chambers
of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI), a leading organization of Nepali
businessmen, on the occasion asked the government to consult with
the private sector while introducing new economic measures.
</P>
<P>
On the controversial issue of Value Added Tax (VAT) regime,
which the government vowed to implement from July this year
despite the private sector's objection, Jyoti said businessmen
would resort to protests if the government turns a deaf ear to
them.
</P>
<P>
The local business community has called a general strike in the
capital city on Wednesday to protest the government's decision to
impose the VAT tax.  
</P>
</TEXT>
