<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party to Back UF Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Congress party leadership
decided on Monday night to restore support to the 13-party United
Front (UF) for the formation of a new government, the Hindustan
Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The party, at a meeting of its supreme decision making body,
the Congress Working Committee (CWC), also decided to withdraw its
claim to form a government before the president as soon as the
front elected a new leader to replace caretaker prime minister H.
D. Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party formally staked the claim soon after it
withdrew its support to the 10-month-old UF government on March
30.
</P>
<P>
The CWC made it clear that it was opposed to a mid-term poll
and the party would not stake its claim to form a government
provided the UF changed its leader.
</P>
<P>
The CWC, which met for two-and-a-half hours late Monday night,
authorized party president Sitaram Kesri to constitute a team to
talk to the UF to sort out all irritants after the front elected
its new leader.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deve Gowda confirmed on Monday that he had
offered to resign from the UF parliamentary group leadership to
pave the way for a new arrangement between the UF and the Congress
party.
</P>
<P>
The UF is expected to elect a successor to the prime minister
later this week.
</P>
<P>
The CWC did not specify whether the Congress party will join
the new government or not.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
