<HEADLINE> Ruling Partner in Nepal Reaffirms Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's major ruling partner
has reaffirmed its support to Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur
Chand's coalition government amid rumors that efforts are being
made to topple the coalition.
</P>
<P>
A senior leader of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML), the biggest party of the three-party
coalition, said here Monday that his party will extend its
full-fledged support to the government under Chand, who is from
the National Democratic Party (RPP).
</P>
<P>
The RPP party, with its 19 MPs in the 205-seat lower house, is
the third largest party in parliament as the CPN-UML and the
Nepali Congress (NC) hold 90 and 88 seats respectively.
</P>
<P>
The present government had been formed in order to give a
positive direction to national politics and adopt people-oriented
programs, CPN-UML General Secretary Madhav Kumar Nepal told a
press conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
He denied the rumors that there are differences within the
CPN-UML on the formation of the coalition government last month.
</P>
<P>
Recent rumors here said that some leaders of the CPN-UML and
the opposition NC party are holding negotiations for a new
government of the two parties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
