<HEADLINE> Dini Stresses Humanitarian Aim of Multinational Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The mission of the multinational
force in Albania would be a humanitarian one, Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini stressed today during a meeting with his
Albanian counterpart, Arjan Starova.
</P>
<P>
The Italian-led 6,000-strong force designed to safeguard the
delivery of humanitarian relief supplies, will not disarm local
gangs, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Starova thanked Italy and seven other countries contributing
troops to the force. The other contributors are France, Spain,
Greece, Turkey, Austria, Romania and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Dini said the presence of the multinational force might bring
confidence to the Albanian people that they would survive the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
It also showed the determination of the Organization of
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and European Union (EU)
to help the ravaged country get back on its feet, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the first large contingent of the force was expected
to arrive in the troubled country Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the force, Italian Admiral Guido Venturoni, said
that the soldiers, 450 from France, 350 Spaniards and 450
Italians, would land at Durres, the country's largest port, on
Tuesday morning. 
</P>
