<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Minister on Peru' Withdrawal From Andean Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Peru's withdrawal from
the Andean Community will not affect the subregional trade bloc
but will prompt its talks with the South American Common Market
(Mercosur), a Colombian minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Peru's departure will not affect in any way the trade
development among the community's other member countries which
are Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador and Venezuela, Colombian Foreign
Trade Minister Carlos Ronderos said in a statement to the RCN
radio network.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori announced Friday that
Peru would quit the Andean Group, claiming that the free-trade
bloc is not living up to its mission of creating freer trade in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said generating jobs and improving Peru's productive
capacity were top priorities, and achieving "those important
goals cannot be ensured continuing to work inside the Andean
Group under current conditions."
</P>
<P>
However, Peru's decision came after other members of the trade
bloc refused to allow Lima exemptions from the free-trade
regime. They said Peru has not complied with its commitments in
the Andean Group which recently renamed itself the Andean
Community.
</P>
<P>
Ronderos said that, contrary to what people might think, the
subregional group was completely fortified because there is a
"Bolivarian" union among the four countries that do not have any
differences and will respond positively to the principles of a
free trade area.
</P>
<P>
He believed that it would now be easier to negotiate with the
Mercosur, formed by Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay, for
there are clear rules that provide a better environment for
carrying out talks and consolidating a South American Free Trade
Area.
</P>
<P>
From now on, he pointed out, a very interesting phase will
begin for the new Andean Pact whose objective is to fortify
itself completely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
