<HEADLINE> Manila Denies MNLF Men's Massive Defection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military has
dismissed as "mere propaganda" earlier reports that more than
5,000 Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) fighters have joined
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), local press reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces Chief of Staff Gen. Arnulfo Acedera was quoted as
saying Monday that the MILF was likely churning out defection
reports to cover up its thinning ranks.
</P>
<P>
He noted MILF rebels have been surrendering to the military in
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
He also said the armed forces have yet to receive an official
report of MNLF members joining the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said about 5,000 MNLF fighters have joined the
MILF after being "discouraged" over the slow implementation of the
peace deal struck last September between the MNLF and Manila.
</P>
<P>
With the joining of the MNLF men, the MILF's force has
increased from some 10,000 to 15,000, becoming the largest
anti-government group in the country.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the MNLF, refused to accept
the peace agreement between the MNLF and the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF began its own peace talks with the government late
last year, but the talks have been stalled due to sporadic
fighting between the MILF guerrillas and the government troops in
the southern Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
