<HEADLINE> Petitions to be Debated by Austrian Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Two high-profile petitions have
collected enough signatures needed for the Austrian parliament to
debate on them, Minister of Interior Affairs Karl Schloegl
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The petitions, one on genetic enginering food and the other on
women rights, were sponsored by the environmentalists and the
feminists in the country.
</P>
<P>
They have collected 1,226,511 and 644,977 signatures
respectively, outnumbering the required 100,000 each to be put on
the parliament agenda.
</P>
<P>
The environmentalists' petition strongly objects the marketing
of genetically altered farm products, including potatoes and corn
in Austria, while the feminist petitioners are demanding that both
sexes have equal educational rights, equal pay in work place and
shared-responsibility at home. 
</P>
