<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Backs Out of China Resolution at UN Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government announced
today that Canada will not co-sponsor a resolution on China's
human rights situation at a meeting of the United Nations
Commission on Human Rights in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"The government has decided, in light of the significant
weakening in consensus on the resolution among its traditional
co-sponsors, that it no longer carries the same weight it has in
past years," said Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
"Under the circumstances, we concluded that Canada could have a
greater influence on the state of human rights in China by
pursuing and intensifying our promising bilateral measures,"
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
"Through intensified dialogue with the Chinese government,
an agreement was reached on the establishment of a joint
Canada-China human rights committee, which will address all human
rights issues including religious freedom," he added.
</P>
<P>
The commitment also included a wider array of projects on legal
reform and institution building, such as Canadian assistance to
develop a legal aid system. It included more training of Chinese
judges, work towards implementation of China's obligations under
the United Nations Convention on Torture, and co-operative work on
minority affairs, the release said.
</P>
<P>
"Agreement with China on this package of bilateral co-operation
is an important development in our relations," the minister
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Follow-ups to Human Rights Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Alternate Representative of the
Chinese delegation Li Baodong said today that a lot of follow-up
work remains to be done although the international community has
made great efforts since the World Conference on Human Rights in
1993.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd session of the United Nations Commission
on Human Rights, Li said, "At present, how to further put into
practice the Vienna Declaration and Program of Action, and to pave
the way for the smooth follow-up to the World Conference has
become a priority facing the international community as well as
this commission."
</P>
<P>
Li said that any attempt to misinterpret the Vienna Declaration
and Program of Action, either by quoting a section out of context,
or stressing certain section at the expense of the other, should
be prevented.
</P>
<P>
Certain countries emphasize only civil and political rights and
neglect economic, social and cultural rights; They play down
development while talking about democracy and human rights. They
set their minds merely on the universality of human rights, paying
little attention to the national, regional, historical and
cultural particularities, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
This line of action is obviously not conducive to the follow-up
to the conference, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is stated in the Vienna Declaration and Program of
Action that democracy, development and respect for human rights and
fundamental freedoms are interdependent and mutually reinforcing,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
"We in China have learned from our own experience of reform and
opening-up that only by concentrating our efforts on economic
development under the precondition of national and social
stability, while sparing no efforts in the building-up of
democracy and legal system, will a country like ours be able to
achieve steady progress and full enjoyment of all human rights by
its people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Any lopsided emphases of one factor while neglecting another,
or any development strategy or democracy model copied blindly in
disregard of one's own national conditions are bound to bring
about adverse effects to the full enjoyment of various human
rights and fundamental freedoms by the people, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Li called for dialogues and cooperation in the international
field of human rights on the basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
At the 51st session of the UN General Assembly, the resolution
entitled Enhancement of International Cooperation in the Field of
Human Rights was adopted by an overwhelming majority of votes, Li
recalled.
</P>
<P>
"This is a clear indication of developing countries' strong
demand to replace confrontation by dialogue and cooperation on
human rights issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some Western countries pay lip service when they say that they
are not in favor of confrontation and what they are doing have
time and again deviated from the spirit of cooperation embodied in
the Vienna Declaration, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li urged the countries concerned to positively respond to the
demand of the developing countries for cooperation, dialogue and
consensus and give up their erroneous approach of confrontation in
the human rights field to join the developing countries for
progress in the international protection of human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
