<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (23-24) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (23-24)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: How will residents of the Hong Kong SAR participate
in the administration of state affairs?
</P>
<P>
Answer: After China resumes its exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, Chinese citizens among Hong Kong residents will become
masters of the country and enjoy the basic rights and freedoms
that citizens of a sovereign state are entitled to.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Article 21 of the Basic Law stipulates,
"Chinese citizens who are residents of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region shall be entitled to participate in the
management of state affairs according to law. In accordance with
the assigned number of seats and the selection method specified by
the National People's Congress, Chinese citizens among residents
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region shall locally elect
deputies of the Region to the National People's Congress to
participate in the work of the highest organ of state power."
</P>
<P>
Question: Will it be convenient for people bearing passports of
the Hong Kong SAR to travel outside the region?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Hong Kong people have a fast pace of life. Travelling
is a favourite holiday activity for many of them. Because of Hong
Kong's special status, people there have long enjoyed the freedom
to travel.
</P>
<P>
In the light of realities in Hong Kong, the Basic Law
stipulates that, after 1997, Hong Kong people, whether they were
born before or after 1997, be issued passports of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region of China. With this passport, a Hong
Kong resident can conveniently go to various countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
As a free port and a financial and trade center, and as a
bridge between China's inland areas and the rest of the world,
Hong Kong has a special place in the world.
</P>
<P>
Foreign countries and regions, out of concern for their own
interests, will naturally recognize the passports of the Hong Kong
SAR and provide convenience for holders of such passports.
</P>
<P>
According to Article 155 of the Basic Law, the central
government will assist or authorize the Hong Kong SAR government
to conclude visa abolition agreements with foreign states or
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
