<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Provides Better Cultural Life For Overseas Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- More overseas residents in Beijing
are enjoying their stay thanks to the introduction of a variety of
media programs.
</P>
<P>
Everyday they can watch fifty minutes of special TV programs of
news and reports made by the local Beijing TV Station in seven
languages--English, Japanese, Russian, French, German, Arabian, and
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
Through these TV programs they are able to know China better
and learn how other overseas residents--students, diplomats, and
corporate representatives live in China.
</P>
<P>
The local Beijing People's Radio also broadcasts regular
English news and other programs, to help overseas guests get more
information and feel like home.
</P>
<P>
In almost every lobby of hotels, office buildings, and
apartments buildings for overseas guests, one can get a free copy
of books and picture albums featuring Beijing or China. Last year
the related departments in Beijing provided more than one million
copies of books and picture albums edited in different languages to
the above places.
</P>
<P>
Currently Beijing hosts more than 6,000 overseas organs and
more than 10,000 overseas funded enterprises. Every year the city
receives more than two million overseas visitors, and some 40,000
overseas nationals work in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
