<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News of The Mercosur (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's Chamber of Industries (CIU, its
acronym in Spanish) demanded last Thursday greater coordination
between Mercosur ministers to prevent the application of
measures such as the import restrictions imposed by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
He requested that a Mercosur Intra-ministerial Council be
formed so there will be greater coordination of macroeconomic
policies.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, the CIU also announced an upcoming
meeting of the Mercosur Industrial Council (CIM, its acronym in
Spanish) in which the presidents of the four industrial
associations of that trade bloc will sign the statement proposed
by the CIU to reject the Brazil's measures.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- On April 9 the Argentine government renewed
its intention to resolve its trade dispute with Brazil by
proposing a harmonious financing system for imports.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's Industry Minister Alieto Guadagni said that he
sent a letter to his Brazilian counterpart Francisco Dornelles
recommending the use of a tool approved in 1995 by the
Mercosur Common Market Group (GMC, its acronym in Spanish) that
gives equal and consensual control over financing.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan senate approved a bill on the
agreement between Uruguay and the Mercosur so that its
Administrative Secretariat will be based in Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat was created through a protocol addendum to
the Asunction Treaty over the institutional structure of the
Mercosur, signed in Ouro Preto, Brazil in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Uruguay's aspiration to create a body with
supranational powers that will resolve Mercosur trade disputes
does not have the support of Argentine Presient Carlos Menem.
</P>
<P>
On April 6 the Argentine press published Menem's statements
that "the Mercosur is a tariff union and not a territorial unit
like the one Europe has wanted to be since the beginning of its
integration."
</P>
<P>
"Furthermore, there is a much simpler recourse than the
creation of a court, which is my permanent contact with Fernando
Henrique (Cardoso, the Brazilian president), that, up till now,
has had good results," underlined Menem.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- On April 4 Uruguay signed the Protocol for
the Solution of Disputes of the Latin American Integration
Association (ALADI, its acronym in Spanish) through which its
can enjoy the preferential treatment of Brazil's new credit
regulations on imports.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's ratification (the only one missing of the ALADI
countries), confirms that this protocol will be able to become
effective on May 4 as part of the agreement on reciprocal credits
and payments.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the protocol will enable that, as in the case of
the other members of the Mercosur, Uruguay will benefit from the
exemptions to the credit regulations on Brazilian imports.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- If Brazil "does not understand that it is a
member of a real common market," Uruguay "will have to seek other
kinds of solutions, such as the Free Trade Area of the Americas
(FTAA) or any other open market relation," said Daniel
Soloducho, president of the Uruguayan Exporters Union (UEU) last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He aruged the need to seek other markets outside of the
region so that Uruguay's foreign trade will not have to depend on
the vicissitudes of Argentina and Brazil's economies.
</P>
<P>
"Uruguay should be as open as possible to the world," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan Economy Minister Luis Mosca confirmed
last Friday that he agreed wtih his Brazilian counterpart
Pedro Malan on the application of a permanent bilateral mechanism
of consultation and coordination that will complement the one
already existing in the Mercosur at the level of economy ministers
and central bank presidents.
</P>
<P>
Mosca expressed his confidence that the meeting on a
multilateral mechanism to be held in Asuncion, Paraguay this April
23 will lead to a solution of the restrictive measures imposed by
Brazil on goods and products imported from its Mercosur partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
