<HEADLINE> U.S. to Help Restore Stability in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States will take
measures to help restore stability in disaster-stricken Albania, a
U.S. official has said in Macedonia's capital city of Skoplje.
</P>
<P>
John Kornblum, the U.S. assistant secretary of state for
European and Canadian affairs, made the remarks at a press
conference on Sunday after meeting with Macedonian President Kiro
Gligorov, and Foreign Minister Ljubomir Frckovski.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not think the crisis in Albania would expand to
other countries, the Macedonian press center reported.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a lasting peace in southeast Europe, however, it was
necessary to maintain stability and prosperity in the region, in
particular, in Albania, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the U.S. would make efforts to help the United
Nations Protective Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) remain in the
Macedonia, a former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of pyramid savings schemes in Albania sparked
massive protests early this year, which turned into armed revolt
in early March. More than 150 people have been killed in the
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
