<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, US to Make Compromise on Pork Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 15 (Xinhua) -- A compromise agreement is being
worked out on the United States' complaint against Philippine
market access commitments under the World Trade Organization, the
local newspaper Business World reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier interview with the newspaper, Agriculture
Assistant Secretary Marinela Castillo said the compromise accord
was raised during bilateral talks held in Manila early this month.
</P>
<P>
He said the accord will be discussed further and finalized in
the Geneva meeting this month. But he declined to give details of
the compromise agreement.
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute arose from a U.S. complaint alleging Manila
has been reneging on its commitment to allow a specified volume of
pork and poultry products imports at preferential tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials criticized Manila's system of assigning the bulk
of pork import allocations to local pork producers who are not
expected to prefer importing a product that would directly compete
with their own.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has already filed an official complaint
with the dispute settlement body of the WTO in Geneva. Prior to
formal hearings by the body, however, the two parties are given
time to settle the matter out of court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
