<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic News Of The Mercosur (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Mercosur and European Union
entrepreneurs get together.
</P>
<P>
MONETVIDEO -- Representatives of more than 500 companies from
the Southern Common Market (Mercosur, its acronym in Spanish)
and the European Union (EU) will gather in this city this
December 4 and 5 for the first "European Union-Mercosur
Partnership" forum.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinetti
recently announced that the gathering will promote the exchange of
products and technologies and services through joint investments,
cooperation agreements, transfers of technology, and manufacturing
licences, etc.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Negotiations for a free trade area between the
Mercosur and the EU will begin in 1999, announced Uruguayan
Foreign Minister Alvaro Ramos on returning to the country last
Friday after attending the VII ministerial meeting between the
Rio Group and the EU in Noordwijk, Holland.
</P>
<P>
He said that 1997 will be the year in which a diagnosis of
the initial situation of both trade blocs can be completed on
three issues: the sale of goods, the sale of services and
commercial disciplines.
</P>
<P>
Once a diagnosis has been completed, they will tackle
negotiating positions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Mercosur has achieved notable success in
expanding its trade and investments with its partners but must
still overcome serious challenges, says a report by the Institute
for the Integration of Latin America and the Caribbean (INTAL,
its acronym in Spanish), an independent body of the
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB).
</P>
<P>
Intal economists stated that the Mercosur "is the most
successful example of integration in Latin America and a model
of open regionalism."
</P>
<P>
The report points out that the common market stimulates the
flow of private investment among its member countries, a
phenomenon that he described as mostly absent in previous
integration attempts.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Hungarian President Arpad Gonzo recently
emphasized here the need to increase bilateral trade with
Argentina as a springboard for greater exchanges between that
European nation and the Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
During his official visit to Argentina, Gonzo underlined his
country's interest in reaching the Mercosur and stressed that
Hungary has a strategic geographical location since it is the
gateway to eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Spanish President Jose Maria Aznar will pay an
official visit to Brazil between April 16-19 which will have an
economic and entrepreneurial focus.
</P>
<P>
On April 20, Aznar will travel to Argentina to continue his
tour and will remain there until April 22.
</P>
<P>
Aznar's tour through the two countries reflects Spain's and
the Euorpean Union's keen interest in the Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The mayors of the capital cities of Mercosur
member countries will meet in this city on April 18 and 19.
</P>
<P>
At the meetings they will analyze the juridical-budgetary
relations between capital cities and central governemnts.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the municipal leaders will sign the
"Declaration of Brasilia" at the end of their meeting.
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- Paraguay called an urgent meeting of economy
ministers and central bank presidents of the Mercosur for April
23 to discuss the trade restrictions adopted by Brazil,
Paraguayan Finance Minister Miguel Maidana said recently.
</P>
<P>
He explained that different issues will be dealt with at the
meeting with emphasis on Brazil's import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
He said that they have already notified Brazilian Economy
Minister Pedro Malan of the meeting. Malan said he "understood
our situation but asked us for detailed analytical studies before
taking any measures," added Maidana. (to be continued)


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
