<HEADLINE> Canadians Keep Clean Slate in Curling World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada clinched two more victories
to keep its clean slate as the World Curling Championship entered
the third day competition in Bern, Switzerland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In their ambition to claim a fifth world title, the Canadians
opened the day with an 8-5 win over winless Australia before
beating the United States 7-5, boosting their record to a perfect
4-0.
</P>
<P>
The American foursome stood 1-3 in a miserable position.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Denmark were the other two teams remained unbeaten
as Denmark gained easy wins over Switzerland and Finland, and
Germany sailed over Norway 5-4 and downed Sweden 12-3.
</P>
<P>
In the women's events, the Canadians remain the only unbeaten
team with an unblemished record of 4-0, living up to the world
titles won in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
They surged to a 7-4 win over Japan and a 7-5 victory over
hosts Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The United States had its first win of the tournament by
clouding Scotland 10-2 in a third round play before a 5-8 defeat
to Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Danish and Norwegian women chased Canada in the standings
with 3-1. 
</P>
