<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Support UN Session on Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of
developing countries today reiterated their support for the
convening of an emergency special session of the General Assembly
so as to save the peace process in the Middle East and stop
Israeli construction in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Committee on the Exercise of the Inalienable
Rights of the Palestinian People, Permanent Observer for Palestine
Nasser al-Kidwa said that the serious situation in the Meddle East
had resulted from the actions of Israel, especially the plans for
its illegal settlement in Jabal Abu Ghneim, as well as its illegal
activities in general in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
The new Israeli settlement, located to the south of east
Jerusalem, was designed to bring in 25,000 Israeli settlers. It
would isolate the Arab neighborhoods and the holy city from the
rest of the West Bank, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is continuously deteriorating. The peace process
is in danger and that constitutes a threat to international peace
and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
As other efforts to stop construction had failed because of
vetoes cast by the United States at the Security Council, al-Kidwa
said, there remained one resort -- to call for a special emergency
session of the General Assembly to recommend necessary and
appropriate means to end Israel's illegal actions and save the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Iabra Deguene Ka of Senegal, chairman of the committee, was
committed to doing everything possible to save the peace process
and support it at such a critical phase.
</P>
<P>
Bruno Rodriguez-Parilia of Cuba said that the assembly and all
of its member states were obligated to shoulder specific
responsibilities regarding the situation in Palestine. The General
Assembly should use its powers to ensure compliance with
commitments assumed in the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qiyue of China said that her country had always supported
the just cause of the Palestinian people. Her delegation had
already sent a letter to the UN secretary-general in support of an
emergency session. She hoped that such a session would be convened
shortly, given the deteriorating situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Marty Muliana Natalegawa of Indonesia said that as chairman of
the Islamic Group, his country had submitted a formal letter
supporting the convening of the session.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of other countries also noted the firm
commitment to Palestine at the recent Non-Aligned Movement meeting
in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Group submitted a request for an emergency special
session of the General Assembly on March 30. Following the action,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan sent a memo to member states
requesting their views on the request. The convening of such a
session needs 94 positive responses from the 185 UN member states.
So far, the UN Secretariat has received 60 letters supporting the
special session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Should Model Itself on Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The president of the Federal
Federation of German Industry (BDI) today said that Germany should
learn more from successful foreign countries in conducting
courageous economic reforms to overcome domestic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the world's largest industrial fair opened to the
public today in Hannover, BDI President Hans-Olaf Henkel said that
it was high time for German decision makers to learn from
successful foreign experiences so long as demanded by
globalization.
</P>
<P>
As an example, Henkel mentioned the United States, which had
managed to overcome economic difficulties in the 1970s and
achieved "unequaled employment dynamic" nowadays.
</P>
<P>
Another good model listed by Henkel was Sweden, which had
conducted fundamental reforms of its problematic welfare systems
and had clearly reduced its unemployment over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Many countries had showed "how people can change course through
courageous reforms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany is now plagued by a post-war record high of
unemployment and high labor costs which have driven much of
investment out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Fully aware of the urgency of the current situation, political
parties in Bonn however still have great difficulties in agreeing
on what should be done to improve it.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the Hannover Fair Sunday
evening, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl described the planned tax
reforms and a promotion of job-creating investment as the most
urgent tasks of his government.
</P>
<P>
But whether such tasks could be fulfilled would heavily depend
on whether a quick compromise could be found during the tax reform
negotiations due to be resumed Tuesday between leaders of the
government and the main opposition Social Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
