<HEADLINE> US Urges Zairian Government, Rebels to Negotiate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States today urged
the Zairian government and rebels to negotiate a solution to their
conflict as rebel leader Laurent Kabila "appears to have momentum"
in his struggle against President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
"We hope very much that Mr Kabila, the rebel forces, and the
government will agree to continue those negotiations under the
auspices of the United Nations, and we hope those talks will start
again soon," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
As the rebel forces continue extending their offensive, Zaire
"risks falling apart under the strains of this civil war, under
the strain of the humanitarian crisis in the north and of the
political chaos in Kinshasa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burns said rebel leader Kabila "does not have much of a track
record as a leader of a government," but the United States will
try "to do our very best in influencing him to be an open leader
if he does become the leader."
</P>
<P>
Last week, the White House indicated that the United States
would not support Mobutu as he "is about to become a creature of
history." 
