<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Speaker Blasts Israeli Policy on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Middle East peace process
is undergoing a retrogression due to Israel's hardline policy
which has faltered peace talks in the region, Speaker of the
Lebanese National Assembly Nabih Berri said in the Qatari capital
of Doha today.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Doha, Berri also said
that Lebanon firmly opposes the Israeli occupation in south
Lebanon and it will fight until the Israeli troops withdraw from
the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held in Doha today, the Lebanese
speaker, who was on a three-day visit to Qatar, said the peace
process is turning backwards because the Israeli government
rejected the principle of peace.
</P>
<P>
"The Netanyahu government refused to accept the Madrid peace
principles and it also rejected negotiations with Palestinians,
leading the peace process to a great retrogression," Berri said.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians were
suspended after the Israeli government decided in February to
build a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which
Palestinians want to be the capital of their future state. The
decision soon sparked wide-spread protests violence that have
continued so far.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing to prove that Israel is going forward for a
just peace and we found that after (former Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak) Rabin's assassination, Israel has not been prepared for
the acception of peace in the region," the Lebanese speaker said.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was assassinated by a Jewish extremist in November of
1995.
</P>
<P>
Asked what his country will do towards Israeli in view of the
Israeli intransigent hardline policy, Berri said that Lebanon will
continue fight Israel until it withdraws all its troops from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We will use two hands, one is U.N. Security Council resolution
425 and another is resistance against Israel's occupation (in
south Lebanon)," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel could not stay in the south part of his
country for too long because most of the Lebanese are against its
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Berri, who arrived in Doha Saturday, held talks with a number of
senior Qatari officials on bilateral ties and the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
