<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Mission in Angola to Be Extended, Transformed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today recommended that the Security Council extend the
mandate of the UN peacekeeping force in Angola until June 30 and
then transform it into an observer mission.
</P>
<P>
The largest UN peacekeeping force, known as the UN Angola
Verification Mission (UNAVEM III), was established by the Security
Council to help implement the 1994 Lusaka Protocol ending the
two-decade civil war. It consists of nearly 5,500 persons now,
compared to over 7,000 during its peak period. Its current mandate
will expire Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that the United Nations Observer Mission in
Angola be formally established on July 1, though he has not
specified the size of the new mission.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the swearing-in last Friday of a government of
unity and national reconciliation, Annan said, "The developments
of the last two weeks in Angola have been very encouraging. Never
before has the country been so close to the final resolution of
its devastating conflict and to the attainment of lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the sincere hope that rapid progress could be made
in completing the implementation of other aspects of the Lusaka
Protocol in a spirit of cooperation and mutual accommodation.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that the long-awaited meeting between President
Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi, leader of the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), would soon
take place.
</P>
<P>
With establishment of the Government of Unity and National
Reconciliation, the parties should move expeditiously to normalize
state administration throughout the whole country, to complete the
formation of the unified armed forces and national police, as well
as to demobilize the excess UNITA military personnel, Annan noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
