<DOCNO> XIE19970415.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Up to Bosnians Themselves, US Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Senior U.S. officials today
rejected criticism of not doing enough for building peace in
Bosnia, saying that the responsibility rests on its own people.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how sincere the engagement of the international
community and the United States, building peace is the
responsibility of Bosnians," said John Kornblum, the outgoing
assistant secretary of state for Europe and Canada and also
special US envoy to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Kornblum and his successor Robert Gelbard were visiting
Sarajevo as part of their tour of the Balkan countries. Kornblum
made more than 20 trips to Bosnia last year to press the Bosnian
parties into compliance with provisions of the Dayton peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his farewell reception, Kornblum noted that while
progress has been made on implementing the Dayton accords by the
Bosnian sides, "far too much energy is still going into individual
gain and the pursuit of rancor rather than actively working to
build the central institutions of a modern nation."
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the criticism in the Bosnian press and by some
Bosnian officials that the international community has not done
enough to help create a new and functional Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He said, "No amount of political will or resources from the
international community can achieve the tolerance and economic and
political security envisioned by the (Dayton) Peace Agreement."
</P>
<P>
"It is the Bosnians of all backgrounds who have a real
self-interest in showing enough statesmanship and commitment to
work for a peaceful future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard said that the United States has never been so engaged
both politically and financially in the Balkan region and "as
practical capitalists, we expect to see return on this
investment."
</P>
<P>
The return should be in the form of Bosnia's development and
peace, capable of taking their place fully in Europe, contributing
to, instead of detracting from, the stability of the region, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard also said that the United States and its allies cannot
impose peace and national reconciliation on Bosnia and "ultimately
it is up to the people of Bosnia and Hercegovina to use their
great capacity to fulfill the promises" in the Dayton accords.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
