<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Proposes New Code on "Sweatshops" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
proposed a code of conduct today to help improve working
conditions in the U.S. apparel industry.
</P>
<P>
Joined by a task force of human rights groups, unions,
religious leaders and a few clothing manufacturers, Clinton urged
U.S. companies to adhere to the voluntary standards so children
and adults won't have to work long hours for abysmally low pay.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the code include a guaranteed minimum wage pegged
to existing standards in individual nations, a maximum 60-hour
work week with at least one day off, and an independent monitor of
conditions in overseas factories used by U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
The code also would bar harassment and abuse in the workplace
and prohibit using workers younger than 15. It would allow
participating companies to use a "no sweatshops" label on their
garments.
</P>
<P>
"We support the proposition that businesses are in business to
make a profit," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that in order for the code to succeed, it must
be embraced throughout the apparel industry. "We know sweatshop
labor will not vanish overnight," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
