<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Not to Go to Iran for OIC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
will not go to Iran for the forthcoming summit of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) scheduled for December
here, a senior Iraqi diplomat said today.
</P>
<P>
Salah N. Al-Samarmad, Charge D'affaires of the Iraqi embassy,
told Xinhua in an exclusive interview that the Iraqi president
will not come here despite the invitation by Iranian President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
However, he said one of Iraq's vice-presidents will come here
for the OIC summit.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati
will go to Baghdad and deliver Rafsanjani's invitation to his
Iraqi counterpart Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Iran formerly planned to send Roads and Transport Minister
Akbar Torkan to Baghdad for the mission, he added, but now
Velayati will go instead because of Thursday's verdict by the
Berlin court ruling that Iranian leaders gave the order for the
killing of four Kurdish opposition leaders in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The verdict triggered demonstrations against Germany in Iran
over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi diplomat said that the forthcoming visit by the
Iranian foreign minister would indicate the improvement of the
relations between Baghdad and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "the Iranian foreign minister should first
go to Baghdad because the invitation was extended to him two
years ago. His visit will be followed by the trip of the Iraqi
foreign minister."
</P>
<P>
Al-Samarmad admitted that both Iraq and Iran have the
intention to improve their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill gesture, he added, the Iraqi side will soon
release 64 Iranian prisoners who were captured in southern Iraq
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iran earlier claimed that Iraq still holds more than 15,000
Iranian POWs according to the documents it has. But Iraq repeatedly
rejected the claim.
</P>
<P>
Iranian authorities said that the remains of 20 Iranian
soldiers killed in the Iranian-Iraqi war from 1980 to 1988 will be
exchanged for the remains of 55 Iraqi soldiers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the desire of the two sides to improve the bilateral
relations, there are several obstacles to block the two countries
to improve their ties, namely: the issue of prisoners of war
(POW), the support of each other's opposition groups, the war
reparations and the return of Iraqi aircraft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
