<HEADLINE> US Dollar Rallies in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rallied late
today to a 38-month high against the mark and rose sharply in
other dealings after remarks by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
incited a selloff in European currencies.
</P>
<P>
The dollar reached an intraday high of 1.7300 marks, the
strongest since February 1994, after Rubin spoke in Washington. It
settled in New York at 1.7298, up from 1.7201 Friday. The dollar
cost 126.20 yen, up from 126.03. The pound cost 1.6210 U.S.
dollars, down from 1.6284 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
During his appearance at a news conference, Rubin said U.S.
support for a strong dollar hasn't changed. But he didn't rule out
intervention to keep the yen from weakening, which is widening
the U.S.-Japan trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
A modest rally in U.S. stock prices, more signs of economic
weakness in Japan and remarks by Japanese officials suggesting
interest rates would remain low also contributed to the dollar's
gain.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Friday: 1.4705
Swiss francs, up from 1.4603; 5.8155 French francs, up from 5.7840;
1,700.75 Italian lire, up from 1,696.25; 1.3992 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.3982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
